# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bulgarian-language
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bulgarian-language/abstand-and-ausbau-languages] In sociolinguistics, an **abstand language** is a language variety or cluster of varieties with significant linguistic distance from all others, while an **ausbau language** is a standard variety, possibly with related dependent varieties.
[src:bulgarian-language/abstand-and-ausbau-languages] This framework addresses situations in which multiple varieties from a dialect continuum have been standardized, so that they are commonly considered distinct languages even though they may be mutually intelligible.
[src:bulgarian-language/abstand-and-ausbau-languages] The continental Scandinavian languages offer a commonly cited example of this situation.
[src:bulgarian-language/abstand-and-ausbau-languages] One of the applications of this theoretical framework is language standardization (examples since the 1960s including Basque and Romansh).
[src:bulgarian-language/abstand-and-ausbau-languages] An *abstand* language is a cluster of varieties that is distinctly separate from any other language.
[src:bulgarian-language/abstand-and-ausbau-languages] European examples include Basque and Breton.
[src:bulgarian-language/abstand-and-ausbau-languages] Kloss also spoke of degrees of *abstand* between pairs of varieties.
[src:bulgarian-language/abstand-and-ausbau-languages] He did not specify how the differences between two varieties would be measured, assuming that linguists would apply objective criteria.
[src:bulgarian-language/abstand-and-ausbau-languages] A standard linguistic criterion is mutual intelligibility, though this does not always produce consistent results, for example when applied to a dialect continuum.
[src:bulgarian-language/abstand-and-ausbau-languages] An *abstand* language does not need to have a standard form.
[src:bulgarian-language/abstand-and-ausbau-languages] This is often the case with minority languages used within a larger state, where the minority language is used only in private, and all official functions are performed in the majority language.
[src:bulgarian-language/abstand-and-ausbau-languages] The German verb *ausbauen* (pronounced [ˈaʊ̯sˌbaʊ̯ən] ⓘ, literally "to build out") expresses core meanings of "expanding" something or "developing something to completion", e.g. adding to an existing structure.
[src:bulgarian-language/abstand-and-ausbau-languages] Kloss identified several stages of this development, beginning with use of the variety for humour or folklore, followed by lyrics and then narrative prose.
[src:bulgarian-language/abstand-and-ausbau-languages] The next phase, which he considered crucial, was use of the variety for serious non-fiction.
[src:bulgarian-language/abstand-and-ausbau-languages] From this point, the variety could be further developed for use in technical, scientific or government domains.
[src:bulgarian-language/abstand-and-ausbau-languages] A standard variety developed in this way can be mutually intelligible with other standard varieties.
[src:bulgarian-language/abstand-and-ausbau-languages] A commonly cited example occurs in the Scandinavian dialect continuum spanning Norway, Sweden and Denmark.
[src:bulgarian-language/abstand-and-ausbau-languages] The three standardized languages Norwegian, Swedish and Danish (or four if Norwegian *Bokmål* and *Nynorsk* are distinguished) are mutually distinct *ausbau* languages, even though speakers of the different standards can, to varying degrees, readily understand one another.
[src:bulgarian-language/abstand-and-ausbau-languages] This classification invokes the criterion of social and political functions of language use.
[src:bulgarian-language/abstand-and-ausbau-languages] The sociolinguist Peter Trudgill has linked Kloss's theoretical framework with Einar Haugen's framework of autonomy and heteronomy, with the statement that a variety is an *ausbau* language corresponding to the statement that it is used "autonomously" with respect to other related languages.
[src:bulgarian-language/abstand-and-ausbau-languages] Such a language has an independent cultural status, even though it may be mutually intelligible with other *ausbau* languages from the same continuum.
[src:bulgarian-language/abstand-and-ausbau-languages] This typically means that it has its own standardized form independent of neighbouring standard languages, it is typically taught in schools, and it is used as a written language in a wide variety of social and political functions, possibly including that of an official national language.
[src:bulgarian-language/abstand-and-ausbau-languages] In contrast, varieties that are not *ausbau* languages are typically only spoken and typically only used in private contexts.
[src:bulgarian-language/abstand-and-ausbau-languages] An Ausbau language is defined by social criteria, and hence tend to treat languages as social constructs that can be identified only through its social status and usage.
[src:bulgarian-language/abstand-and-ausbau-languages] However, the coexistence of abstand and ausbau languages lead to two opposing sets of criteria over the status of nonstandard varieties.
[src:bulgarian-language/abstand-and-ausbau-languages] For example, various varieties of German and Italian are considered dialects according to Ausbau criteria, although they are linguistically distant from the standard languages.
[src:bulgarian-language/abstand-and-ausbau-languages] Kloss described an *ausbau* language as providing a "roof" (German: *Dach*) over dependent varieties, whereas non-standard varieties without a reference standard were "roofless dialects".
[src:bulgarian-language/abstand-and-ausbau-languages] He used the term "near-dialectized sister languages" for varieties roofed by a standard variety with which they are related but not mutually intelligible, such as Low Saxon (roofed by Standard German), Occitan and Haitian Creole (roofed by French), and Sardinian (roofed by Italian).
[src:bulgarian-language/abstand-and-ausbau-languages] A later development is the notion of multiple, pluricentric standards within the same language; for German not one but at least three roofs are offered: Standard German German, Standard Austrian German and Standard Swiss German.
[src:bulgarian-language/abstand-and-ausbau-languages] These newer conceptualizations, however, may be restricted by "One Standard Axioms", which uphold presuppositions of a single standard, a single "Dach", that exert hegemonic power e.g. the "One Standard German Axiom" (OSGA).
[src:bulgarian-language/abstand-and-ausbau-languages] Muljačić introduced the term *Dachsprache*, or "roofing language", for a dialect that serves as a standard language for other dialects.
[src:bulgarian-language/abstand-and-ausbau-languages] These dialects would usually be in a dialect continuum, but may be so different that mutual intelligibility is not possible between all dialects, particularly those separated by significant geographical distance.
[src:bulgarian-language/abstand-and-ausbau-languages] The roofing language may also cover linguistic varieties that are not mutually intelligible with the roofing language, such as in the case of Standard German.
[src:bulgarian-language/abstand-and-ausbau-languages] In order to resolve the difficulty of partitioning a dialect continuum, Goossens as well as Chambers and Trudgill argue that all nonstandard varieties that are under the roofing language should be considered part of the same language as the roofing language.
[src:bulgarian-language/abstand-and-ausbau-languages] In 1982, "Rumantsch Grischun" was developed by Heinrich Schmid as such a *Dachsprache* for a number of quite different Romansh language forms spoken in parts of Switzerland.
[src:bulgarian-language/abstand-and-ausbau-languages] Similarly, Standard Basque and the Southern Quechua literary standard were both developed as standard languages for dialect continua that had historically been thought of as discrete languages with many dialects and no "official" dialect.
[src:bulgarian-language/abstand-and-ausbau-languages] Standard German and Italian, to some extent, function in the same way.
[src:bulgarian-language/abstand-and-ausbau-languages] Perhaps the most widely used *Dachsprache* is Modern Standard Arabic, which links together the speakers of many different, often mutually unintelligible varieties of Arabic.
[src:bulgarian-language/abstand-and-ausbau-languages] The Dachsprache functions together with dialects to form a linguistic diasystem, which consists of different linguistic systems that coexist and mutually influence.
[src:bulgarian-language/abstand-and-ausbau-languages] Within the diasystem, the Dachsprache functions as the standard for interdialectal communication, for example, with Standard Chinese assisting communication between different dialects and influencing their vocabulary.
[src:bulgarian-language/abstand-and-ausbau-languages] Kloss recognized three degrees of separation between ausbau languages.
[src:bulgarian-language/abstand-and-ausbau-languages] When two standards are based on identical or near-identical dialects, he considered them as splits of the same standard into two or more, constituting a pluricentric language.
[src:bulgarian-language/abstand-and-ausbau-languages] Examples include British and American Standard English, Standard Austrian German and German Standard German, or European and Brazilian variants of Portuguese.
[src:bulgarian-language/abstand-and-ausbau-languages] High Hindi and Urdu also have a common dialect basis (Hindustani).
[src:bulgarian-language/abstand-and-ausbau-languages] The same is the case with Serbian, Croatian, Bosnian and Montenegrin, which also have the same dialect basis (Shtokavian), and consequently constitute four standard variants of the pluricentric Serbo-Croatian language.
[src:bulgarian-language/abstand-and-ausbau-languages] Standards created from different dialects, but with little *abstand*, would not be considered separate abstand languages, but constitute distinct ausbau languages, as noted above for Danish, Swedish and Norwegian.
[src:bulgarian-language/abstand-and-ausbau-languages] The concept of *ausbau* is particularly important in cases where the local spoken varieties across a larger region form a dialect continuum.
[src:bulgarian-language/abstand-and-ausbau-languages] In such cases, the question of where the one language ends and the other starts is often a question more of *ausbau* than of *abstand.* In some instances, *ausbau* languages have been created out of dialects for purposes of nation-building.
[src:bulgarian-language/abstand-and-ausbau-languages] This applies, for instance, to Luxembourgish *vis-a-vis* German (the vernaculars in Luxembourg are varieties of Moselle Franconian, which is also spoken in the German sections of the Moselle River valley and neighbouring French département of Moselle).
[src:bulgarian-language/abstand-and-ausbau-languages] Other examples of groups of vernaculars lacking *abstand* internally but that have given rise to multiple *ausbau* languages are: Persian of Iran, Afghanistan and Tajikistan (*cf.* Farsi, Dari, Tajik); Bulgarian and Macedonian, because they have different dialect bases.
[src:bulgarian-language/abstand-and-ausbau-languages] Finally, the *ausbau* languages may be so different that they also constitute *abstand* languages.
[src:bulgarian-language/abstand-and-ausbau-languages] Examples include Dutch versus German, Persian versus Pashto, and Tamil versus Telugu.
[src:bulgarian-language/abstand-and-ausbau-languages] In the former two cases, scholars do not always agree on the best classification, as they always partake, inadvertently, in the "language making" and "language unmaking" process.
[src:bulgarian-language/abstand-and-ausbau-languages] There are several instances of languages and language pairs that have undergone role changes over time.
[src:bulgarian-language/abstand-and-ausbau-languages] Low German, for instance, was both an Ausbau language and a roof of local dialects in the Netherlands, Germany and parts of the Baltic states and their formerly German vicinity.
[src:bulgarian-language/abstand-and-ausbau-languages] With the end of the Hanseatic League, Low German lost its status as an official language to a large degree.
[src:bulgarian-language/abstand-and-ausbau-languages] Approximately at the same time, Dutch started to replace Low German as a roof of the Low German dialects in the Netherlands that form today's Dutch Low Saxon group, and most Central German dialects went under the "roof" of the evolving High German.
[src:bulgarian-language/abstand-and-ausbau-languages] Low German ceased to be spoken on the eastern rim of the Baltic Sea.
[src:bulgarian-language/abstand-and-ausbau-languages] Today, its dialects surviving in northern Germany have come under the roof of Standard German.
[src:bulgarian-language/abstand-and-ausbau-languages] Local Low German dialects spoken in the Netherlands have come under the roof of Dutch.
[src:bulgarian-language/abstand-and-ausbau-languages] This happened despite the effect of notable migration streams in both directions between the Western (Dutch) and Eastern (Prussian, now mainly Polish and Russian) areas of the region of the Low German languages, motivated by both religious intolerance and labour need.
[src:bulgarian-language/abstand-and-ausbau-languages] In several spots along the Dutch–German border, identical dialects are spoken on both sides, but are deemed to belong to different roofing according to which side of the border they are on.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-bulgaria-to-the-european-union] On 1 January 2007, Bulgaria and Romania became member states of the European Union (EU) in the fifth wave of EU enlargement.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-bulgaria-to-the-european-union] Bulgaria and Romania did not have a referendum related to European Union accession.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-bulgaria-to-the-european-union] Romania was the first country of post-communist Europe to have official relations with the European Community.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-bulgaria-to-the-european-union] In 1974, a treaty included Socialist Republic of Romania in the Community's Generalized System of Preferences.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-bulgaria-to-the-european-union] Following the Romanian Revolution of 1989, membership of the EC, and its successor the European Union (EU), had been the main goal of every Romanian Government and practically every political party in Romania.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-bulgaria-to-the-european-union] Romania signed its Europe Agreement in 1993, and submitted its official application for membership in the EU on 22 June 1995 and Bulgaria submitted its official application for membership in the EU on 14 December 1995.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-bulgaria-to-the-european-union] Along with its official EU application, Romania submitted the Snagov Declaration, signed by all fourteen major political parties declaring their full support for EU membership.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-bulgaria-to-the-european-union] The objective of joining the EU also influenced Bulgaria and Romania's regional relations.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-bulgaria-to-the-european-union] As a result, Bulgaria and Romania imposed visa regimes on a number of states, including Russia, Ukraine, Belarus, Serbia, Montenegro, Turkey and Moldova.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-bulgaria-to-the-european-union] Within the framework of integration meetings held between the EU member states and the EU candidate states Bulgaria and Romania, an 'Association Committee' was held on 22 June 2004.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-bulgaria-to-the-european-union] The findings were reflected in the 2004 Regular Report for Bulgaria and Romania.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-bulgaria-to-the-european-union] The Brussels European Council of 17 December 2004 confirmed the conclusion of accession negotiations with Bulgaria and Romania.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-bulgaria-to-the-european-union] With this accession, Cyrillic became the third official alphabet of the EU, after the Latin and Greek alphabets.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-bulgaria-to-the-european-union] Cyrillic will also be featured on the euro banknotes and the national (obverse) side of the Bulgarian euro coins.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-bulgaria-to-the-european-union] The ECB and the EU Commission insisted that Bulgaria change the official name of the currency from ЕВРО (EVRO) (as accepted) to ЕУРО (EURO), claiming that the currency should have a standard spelling and pronunciation across the EU.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-bulgaria-to-the-european-union] For details, see Linguistic issues concerning the euro.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-bulgaria-to-the-european-union] The issue was decisively resolved in favour of Bulgaria at the 2007 EU Summit in Lisbon, allowing Bulgaria to use the Cyrillic spelling евро on all official EU documents.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-bulgaria-to-the-european-union] The date of accession, 1 January 2007, was set at the Thessaloniki Summit in 2003 and confirmed in Brussels on 18 June 2004.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-bulgaria-to-the-european-union] Bulgaria, Romania and the EU-25 signed the Treaty of Accession on 25 April 2005 at Luxembourg's Neumuenster Abbey.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-bulgaria-to-the-european-union] The 26 September 2006 monitoring report of the European Commission confirmed the entry date as 1 January 2007.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-bulgaria-to-the-european-union] The last instrument of ratification of the Treaty of Accession was deposited with the Italian government on 20 December 2006 thereby ensuring it came into force on 1 January 2007.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-bulgaria-to-the-european-union] Bulgaria and Romania became members on 1 January 2007, but the application of some areas of cooperation in the European Union to Bulgaria and Romania were deferred to a later date.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-bulgaria-to-the-european-union] On 1 January 2007, Bulgarian and Romanian nationals became European Union citizens and acquired the right to move and reside freely in other EU member states.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-bulgaria-to-the-european-union] However, some member states of the EU required Bulgarians and Romanians to acquire a permit to work, whilst members of all other old member states did not require one.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-bulgaria-to-the-european-union] In the Treaty of Accession 2005, there was a clause about a transition period so each old EU member state could impose such 2+3+2 transitional periods.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-bulgaria-to-the-european-union] Restrictions were planned to remain in place until 1 January 2014 – 7 years after their accession.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-bulgaria-to-the-european-union] On 1 January 2014, restrictions were lifted in the last remaining member states, giving Bulgarian and Romanian citizens right to work in all EU and EEA member states.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-bulgaria-to-the-european-union] While both countries were admitted, concerns about corruption and organised crime were still high.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-bulgaria-to-the-european-union] As a result, although they joined, they were subject to monitoring from the European Commission through a Mechanism for Cooperation and Verification (CVM).
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-bulgaria-to-the-european-union] It was initially set up for three years after the accession but has continued indefinitely and although it has highlighted the corruption and applied some pressure to continue reforms, it has not succeeded in forcing the two countries to complete reforms and corruption persists.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-bulgaria-to-the-european-union] In 2019 however, the European Commission stated that it will admit Bulgaria in the Schengen area for its efforts against corruption.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-bulgaria-to-the-european-union] The accession treaty granted Bulgaria and Romania a seat, like every other state, on the commission.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-bulgaria-to-the-european-union] Bulgaria nominated Meglena Kuneva, from NDSV who was given the post of Commissioner for Consumer Protection in the Barroso Commission, from 1 January 2007 until 31 October 2009.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-bulgaria-to-the-european-union] She was nominated in 2006 by the then current Bulgarian Prime Minister Sergei Stanishev.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-bulgaria-to-the-european-union] Romania nominated Leonard Orban, an independent, who was made Commissioner for Multilingualism in the Barroso Commission, from 1 January 2007 until 31 October 2009.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-bulgaria-to-the-european-union] He was nominated in 2006 by the previous Romanian Prime Minister Călin Popescu-Tăriceanu.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-bulgaria-to-the-european-union] Both were approved by Parliament to become Commissioners upon accession.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-bulgaria-to-the-european-union] Upon accession Bulgaria's 18 and Romania's 35 observer MEPs became full voting representatives until each state held an election for the posts, which were mandated to happen before the end of the year.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-bulgaria-to-the-european-union] Bulgaria held its election on 20 May 2007 and Romania on 25 November 2007.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-north-macedonia-to-the-european-union-p01] The accession of North Macedonia to the European Union has been on the current agenda for future enlargement of the EU since 2005, when it became an official candidate for accession.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-north-macedonia-to-the-european-union-p01] The then-Republic of Macedonia submitted its membership application in 2004, thirteen years after its independence from Yugoslavia.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-north-macedonia-to-the-european-union-p01] It is one of nine current EU candidate countries, together with Albania, Bosnia and Herzegovina, Georgia, Moldova, Montenegro, Serbia, Turkey and Ukraine.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-north-macedonia-to-the-european-union-p01] The use of the country name "Macedonia" was the object of a dispute with neighbouring Greece between 1991 and 2019, resulting in a Greek veto against EU and NATO accession talks, which lasted from 2008 to 2019.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-north-macedonia-to-the-european-union-p01] After the issue was resolved, the EU gave its formal approval to begin accession talks with North Macedonia and Albania in March 2020.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-north-macedonia-to-the-european-union-p01] On 24 June 2022, Bulgaria's parliament approved lifting the country's veto on opening EU accession talks with North Macedonia.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-north-macedonia-to-the-european-union-p01] On 16 July 2022, the Assembly of North Macedonia also approved the revised French proposal, allowing accession negotiations to begin.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-north-macedonia-to-the-european-union-p01] The start of negotiations was officially launched on 19 July 2022.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-north-macedonia-to-the-european-union-p01] To make progress, however, the country must change its constitution, including local Bulgarians in it, and overcome the latent opposition of neighbouring Bulgaria.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-north-macedonia-to-the-european-union-p01] However, several parties have consistently blocked the parliamentary passage of the required constitutional amendment.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-north-macedonia-to-the-european-union-p01] The agreement was ratified by the Macedonian parliament on 12 April 2001 and came into force on 1 April 2004.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-north-macedonia-to-the-european-union-p01] On 22 March 2004, the Republic of Macedonia submitted its application for EU membership.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-north-macedonia-to-the-european-union-p01] On 6 September 2004, the Macedonian government adopted a National Strategy for European integration, supported by the country's parliament through its Commission for European Issues.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-north-macedonia-to-the-european-union-p01] The government subsequently began the procedure of answering the questionnaire of the European Commission regarding its performance in preparation for membership in accordance with the Copenhagen criteria, a process that was finished by 31 January 2005.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-north-macedonia-to-the-european-union-p01] The European Council officially granted the country candidate status on 17 December 2005, after a review and a positive recommendation of the candidacy by the European Commission.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-north-macedonia-to-the-european-union-p01] After the naming dispute with Greece was solved in 2019, accession negotiations were expected to start within the same year, but in June 2019 the EU General Affairs Council decided to postpone the decision to October, due to objections from a number of countries including the Netherlands and France.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-north-macedonia-to-the-european-union-p01] France vetoed the decision again in October.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-north-macedonia-to-the-european-union-p01] On 25 March 2020 the Council of the European Union decided to open accession negotiations, which was endorsed by the European Council the following day.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-north-macedonia-to-the-european-union-p01] On 17 November 2020 Bulgaria blocked the official start of accession talks with the country.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-north-macedonia-to-the-european-union-p01] North Macedonia was told to offer further guarantees to Bulgaria that it would honour the 2017 friendship treaty, which deals with historical issues.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-north-macedonia-to-the-european-union-p01] A major obstacle for the accession process was the Republic's unresolved objection by Greece over its name, as Greece argued that it implied territorial ambitions towards Greece's own northern province of Macedonia.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-north-macedonia-to-the-european-union-p01] Greece, as any other EU country, has veto power against new accessions, and blocked Macedonian accession due to the naming dispute.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-north-macedonia-to-the-european-union-p01] On 12 June 2018, an agreement was reached between Greek prime minister Alexis Tsipras and his Macedonian counterpart Zoran Zaev, known as the Prespa agreement, under which the country would be renamed the "Republic of North Macedonia".
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-north-macedonia-to-the-european-union-p01] As part of this deal, Greece explicitly withdrew its previous opposition, allowing the EU to approve on 26 June 2018 a pathway to starting accession talks.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-north-macedonia-to-the-european-union-p01] Although Bulgaria was the first country to recognise the independence of the then Republic of Macedonia, most of its academics, as well as the general public, do not recognise the Macedonian language and nation formed after the Second World War as being separate from Bulgarian proper.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-north-macedonia-to-the-european-union-p01] As part of the efforts to find a solution to the Macedonia name dispute with Greece, the Macedonian constitution was changed twice (in 1995, and then again in 2018) to formally exclude any possible territorial aspirations towards neighbouring countries.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-north-macedonia-to-the-european-union-p01] Macedonia and Bulgaria signed a friendship treaty to improve their complicated relations in August 2017.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-north-macedonia-to-the-european-union-p01] A joint commission on historical and educational issues was formed in 2018 to serve as a forum where controversial historical and educational issues could be raised and discussed.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-north-macedonia-to-the-european-union-p01] This commission has made little progress in its work for a period of one year.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-north-macedonia-to-the-european-union-p01] Bulgarian politicians claim North Macedonia remains the only country in NATO, that is an EU-candidate, whose politics is based on communist historical and linguistic dogmas accepted by ASNOM.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-north-macedonia-to-the-european-union-p01] On the other hand, researchers claim that Bulgaria's official positions towards Macedonia are rooted in ideological positions dating back to the communist period under Todor Zhivkov.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-north-macedonia-to-the-european-union-p01] Concerning the Macedonian language, Bulgaria advises the EU to avoid using the term "Macedonian language" during the accession talks, and instead use the term "Official language of Republic of North Macedonia", reaffirming that it does not recognise the language as separate from Bulgarian.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-north-macedonia-to-the-european-union-p01] In North Macedonia this is widely perceived as a direct attack on its national identity and language.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-north-macedonia-to-the-european-union-p01] In September 2020, Bulgaria sent an explanatory memorandum to the Council of the European Union containing its framework position on the accession of North Macedonia.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-north-macedonia-to-the-european-union-p01] Per political scientists Yorgos Christidis and Florian Bieber, and experts from European think tanks such as the Jacques Delors Institute, DGAP, the Clingendael Institute, and Carnegie Europe, the vetoes have undermined the EU's credibility in North Macedonia and across the Western Balkans.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-north-macedonia-to-the-european-union-p01] The vetoes also received condemnation by some Bulgarian intellectuals, and criticism from international observers.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-north-macedonia-to-the-european-union-p01] In June 2022 at the very end of the French Presidency of the Council of the European Union (January–June), an urgent proposal was put out by the president Emmanuel Macron to resolve the dispute between the two countries.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-north-macedonia-to-the-european-union-p01] The proposal provoked a political crisis in Bulgaria.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-north-macedonia-to-the-european-union-p01] On June 8, Slavi Trifonov withdrew his party from Bulgaria's governing coalition, citing the issue of North Macedonia.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-north-macedonia-to-the-european-union-p01] This faced criticism from President Rumen Radev, who said the proposal was relatively good.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-north-macedonia-to-the-european-union-p01] However, the government abdicated its responsibility and delegated it entirely to the parliament.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-north-macedonia-to-the-european-union-p01] As result on 22 June the Bulgarian government faced a motion of no confidence, which it lost.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-north-macedonia-to-the-european-union-p01] Nevertheless, on 24 June, after heated discussions, the parliament approved lifting the veto.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-north-macedonia-to-the-european-union-p01] President Macron claimed that the European leaders had put a lot of pressure on Bulgaria to accept this deal, confirming its approval was a "very good signal".
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-north-macedonia-to-the-european-union-p01] On June 25, the Ministry of Foreign Affairs in Sofia stated that the speed with which North Macedonia would approach the EU membership, already depended on itself.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-north-macedonia-to-the-european-union-p01] Two days before the end of the French presidency of the EU, the Prime Minister of North Macedonia Kovačevski stated that the government remains of the opinion that the agreement proposed from Paris and approved by Bulgaria is unacceptable for the country.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-north-macedonia-to-the-european-union-p01] However, since then, the proposal has been backed by the government of North Macedonia.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-north-macedonia-to-the-european-union-p01] Joseph in 2023, Levica, an Eurosceptic party, has been gaining increasing support among ethnic Macedonians as disillusionment with the EU was building.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-north-macedonia-to-the-european-union-p01] In early July 2022, protests began in North Macedonia against the French proposal.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-north-macedonia-to-the-european-union-p01] However, the proposal was accepted by the Assembly of North Macedonia on 16 July 2022.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-north-macedonia-to-the-european-union-p01] On 17 July 2022 in Sofia, the foreign ministers of Bulgaria and North Macedonia signed a second bilateral protocol to the Treaty of Good Neighborhood and Friendship between the two countries.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-north-macedonia-to-the-european-union-p01] Such protocols were supposed to be signed every year, but in practice they have not been signed since 2019.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-north-macedonia-to-the-european-union-p01] According to the decision of the Bulgarian National Assembly of June 24, the signing of this protocol is a condition for Bulgaria to approve the Negotiating Framework for the Republic of North Macedonia.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-north-macedonia-to-the-european-union-p01] The protocol contains specific measures and deadlines for the implementation of agreements on historical issues between the two countries, measures against hate speech, etc.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-north-macedonia-to-the-european-union-p01] The approved document includes the condition to stop "hate speech" against all "minorities and communities", that North Macedonia recognise a shared history with Bulgaria, and the inclusion of Bulgarian people as a recognised minority in the Constitution.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-north-macedonia-to-the-european-union-p01] On July 17, North Macedonia signed a special protocol with Bulgaria to cooperate on these subjects.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-north-macedonia-to-the-european-union-p01] Following the formal start of accession negotiations in July 2022, the next step is for North Macedonia to meet the conditions to start substantial negotiations by the opening of the first 5 negotiating chapters (*Fundamentals cluster*) at a second intergovernmental conference.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-north-macedonia-to-the-european-union-p01] This step will not begin until the "opening phase" has been completed, which according to the Council conclusions of July 2022 is conditional on the Assembly of North Macedonia approving the agreed constitutional amendment related to the Bulgarian minority.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-north-macedonia-to-the-european-union-p01] A two-thirds majority vote in the Assembly of North Macedonia is needed in order to approve the required constitutional amendment.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-north-macedonia-to-the-european-union-p01] However, VMRO-DPMNE which insisted that the French proposal leads to "Bulgarianisation" of the country, has consistently blocked the passage of the required constitutional amendment and campaigned on the idea that the EU negotiation framework instead should be changed to omit this requirement.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-north-macedonia-to-the-european-union-p01] These policies directly contributed to the party's decisive victory at the elections in May 2024.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-north-macedonia-to-the-european-union-p01] On 25 September 2024, the EU announced the decoupling of Albania from North Macedonia on the EU accession path, due to the disputes between North Macedonia and Bulgaria around the Bulgarian minority in North Macedonia, which had delayed further talks.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-north-macedonia-to-the-european-union-p01] Following the decision on decoupling of their processes, the EU opened negotiations on the first chapters with Albania separately on 15 October 2024.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-north-macedonia-to-the-european-union-p01] According to foreign and domestic experts, Bulgaria's veto widened internal divisions in North Macedonia and turned EU accession prospects into "a nightmare of potentially endless Bulgarian demands".
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-north-macedonia-to-the-european-union-p01] This situation is viewed as "perpetually destabilising for the country" and "a fiasco for EU politics".
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-north-macedonia-to-the-european-union-p01] He also argued that the EU is making a mistake by exerting pressure on North Macedonia to implement the agreement without providing clear guarantees that Bulgaria would adhere to its spirit and refrain from introducing new identity‑related demands.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-north-macedonia-to-the-european-union-p01] In May 2026, the doyen of Macedonian diplomacy, Viktor Gaber, submitted a proposal to the parliament in Skopje to call a referendum to decide on the acceptance of the French proposal and the inclusion of Bulgarians in the country's constitution.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-north-macedonia-to-the-european-union-p01] The idea was also supported by the leader of the opposition SDSM, Venko Filipče.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-north-macedonia-to-the-european-union-p01] However, the government of Hristijan Mickoski refused to hold such a referendum.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-north-macedonia-to-the-european-union-p01] Around the same time, law professor Denko Maleski wrote about the historical dispute with Bulgaria, stating that North Macedonia is distancing itself from the French proposal (including shared history) as a solution to the dispute.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-north-macedonia-to-the-european-union-p01] According to Maleski, the EU stands behind Bulgaria and the Bulgarian interpretation of the shared history with Macedonians.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-north-macedonia-to-the-european-union-p01] In July 2025 the European Parliament adopted a resolution on the report on North Macedonia's progress towards EU accession.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-north-macedonia-to-the-european-union-p01] The accession process was left stalled largely due to unresolved political and legal issues in relations with Bulgaria.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-north-macedonia-to-the-european-union-p01] The report also expressed concern about the roles of the Hungarian and Serbian Governments in advancing China's and Russia's geopolitical influence, and by the role of the "Serbian world" project in the country.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-north-macedonia-to-the-european-union-p01] It was claimed there that some representatives in Mickoski's government have promoted this concept, that aims to establish a Serbian influence on the Balkans.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-north-macedonia-to-the-european-union-p01] On 3 June 2026, the European Parliament's Committee on Foreign Affairs (AFET) adopted its report on North Macedonia, reiterating full support for the country's EU membership aspirations based on measurable progress and strict but fair conditionality.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-north-macedonia-to-the-european-union-p01] North Macedonia has so far received €1.3 billion of development aid until 2020 from the Instrument for Pre-Accession Assistance, a funding mechanism for EU candidate countries.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-north-macedonia-to-the-european-union-p01] In November 2025, a corruption scandal involving the EU‑funded IPARD programme led to the arrest of several officials, including the director of the Agency for Financial Support of Agriculture and Rural Development, on charges of bribery.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-north-macedonia-to-the-european-union-p01] As a result, the European Commission suspended all IPARD III payments to the country.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-north-macedonia-to-the-european-union-p01] Following an audit which found no systemic irregularities, the suspension was lifted in April 2026 and funding was restored.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-north-macedonia-to-the-european-union-p01] The government's motto for the candidacy is "*The Sun, too, is a star.*", referring to the sun from the flag of North Macedonia being displayed among the other stars in the flag of Europe.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-north-macedonia-to-the-european-union-p01] North Macedonia's government has established a management infrastructure for the European integration process on the basis of a paper adopted in 1997 under the title "The strategic bases of the Republic of [North] Macedonia on achieving the membership of the European Union".
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-north-macedonia-to-the-european-union-p01] Around 79% of the population of North Macedonia is in favour of EU accession.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-north-macedonia-to-the-european-union-p01] However, those who think North Macedonia is closer to EU entry today than it was in 2005, when it first received candidate member status, dropped from 57% to 32% between 2018 and 2021.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-north-macedonia-to-the-european-union-p01] According to the 2025 annual survey of opinion in North Macedonia, 65% of citizens have a positive attitude towards the EU (23% very positive, 42% fairly positive), while trust in the EU is 75%.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-north-macedonia-to-the-european-union-p01] It is also revealed that 70% of citizens would vote in favour of North Macedonia's membership of the EU if a referendum was held, while 70% of citizens believe that EU memebership would bring more advantages than disadvantages.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-north-macedonia-to-the-european-union-p01] On 1 January 2008 the visa facilitation and readmission agreements between Macedonia and the EU entered into force.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-north-macedonia-to-the-european-union-p01] Macedonia began a visa liberalisation dialogue with the EU in February 2008 and was added to the list of visa exempt nationals on 19 December 2009, allowing their citizens to enter the Schengen Area and Cyprus without a visa when travelling with biometric passports.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-north-macedonia-to-the-european-union-p01] On 19 November 2024, the European Union and North Macedonia signed a Security and Defence Partnership.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-north-macedonia-to-the-european-union-p02] No chapters have been opened since screening was completed in December 2023.
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-north-macedonia-to-the-european-union-p02] † indicates chapters in which the European Commission has simultaneously awarded the chapter ***both*** "some level of preparation" AND "moderately prepared".
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-north-macedonia-to-the-european-union-p02] ‡ indicates chapters in which the European Commission has simultaneously awarded the chapter ***both*** "moderately prepared" AND "good level of preparation".
[src:bulgarian-language/accession-of-north-macedonia-to-the-european-union-p02] Chapters in **bold** indicate completed chapters.
[src:bulgarian-language/accusative-case] In grammar, the **accusative case** (abbreviated **acc**) of a noun is the grammatical case used to receive the direct object of a transitive verb.
[src:bulgarian-language/accusative-case] In the English language, the only words that occur in the accusative case are pronouns: "me", "him", "her", "us", "whom", and "them".
[src:bulgarian-language/accusative-case] For example, the pronoun *she*, as the subject of a clause, is in the nominative case ("She wrote a book"); but if the pronoun is instead the object of the verb, it is in the accusative case and *she* becomes *her* ("Fred greeted her").
[src:bulgarian-language/accusative-case] For compound direct objects, it would be, e.g., "Fred invited me and her to the party".
[src:bulgarian-language/accusative-case] The accusative case is used in many languages for the objects of (some or all) prepositions.
[src:bulgarian-language/accusative-case] It is usually combined with the nominative case (for example in Latin).
[src:bulgarian-language/accusative-case] The English term, "accusative", derives from the Latin *accusativus*, which, in turn, is a translation of the Greek αἰτιατική.
[src:bulgarian-language/accusative-case] The word can also mean "causative", and that might have derived from the Greeks, but the sense of the Roman translation has endured and is used in some other modern languages as the grammatical term for this case, for example in Russian (винительный).
[src:bulgarian-language/accusative-case] Some Balto-Finnic languages, such as Finnish, have two cases for objects, the accusative and the partitive case.
[src:bulgarian-language/accusative-case] In morphosyntactic alignment terms, both do the accusative function, but the accusative object is telic, while the partitive is not.
[src:bulgarian-language/accusative-case] Modern English almost entirely lacks declension in its nouns; pronouns, however, have an understood case usage, as in *them*, *her*, *him* and *whom*, which merges the accusative and dative functions, and originates in old Germanic dative forms (see Declension in English).
[src:bulgarian-language/accusative-case] In the sentence *The man sees **the dog***, *the dog* is the direct object of the verb "to see".
[src:bulgarian-language/accusative-case] In English, which has mostly lost grammatical cases, the definite article and noun – "the dog" – remain the same noun form without number agreement in the noun either as subject or object, though an artifact of it is in the verb and has number agreement, which changes to "sees".
[src:bulgarian-language/accusative-case] In a declined language, the morphology of the article or noun changes with gender agreement.
[src:bulgarian-language/accusative-case] For example, in German, "the dog" is *der Hund*.
[src:bulgarian-language/accusative-case] This is the form in the nominative case, used for the subject of a sentence.
[src:bulgarian-language/accusative-case] If this article/noun pair is used as the object of a verb, it (usually) changes to the accusative case, which entails an article shift in German – *Der Mann sieht **den Hund*** (The man sees the dog).
[src:bulgarian-language/accusative-case] In German, masculine nouns change their definite article from *der* to *den* in the accusative case.
[src:bulgarian-language/accusative-case] In Nepali, "Rama sees Shyama" would be translated as रामले श्यामलाई देख्छ। *Rama-le Shyama-lai dekhchha.* The same sentence in Sanskrit would be रामः पश्यति श्यामम्। *Rama: pashyati Shyamam*.
[src:bulgarian-language/accusative-case] The accusative case in Latin has minor differences from the accusative case in Proto-Indo-European.
[src:bulgarian-language/accusative-case] For the accusative endings, see Latin declensions.
[src:bulgarian-language/accusative-case] The accusative case is used for the direct object in a sentence.
[src:bulgarian-language/accusative-case] The masculine forms for German articles, e.g., "the", "a/an", "my", etc., change in the accusative case: they always end in -en.
[src:bulgarian-language/accusative-case] The feminine, neutral and plural forms do not change.
[src:bulgarian-language/accusative-case] Some German pronouns also change in the accusative case.
[src:bulgarian-language/accusative-case] The accusative case is also used after particular German prepositions.
[src:bulgarian-language/accusative-case] These include *bis*, *durch*, *für*, *gegen*, *ohne*, *um*, after which the accusative case is always used, and *an*, *auf*, *hinter*, *in*, *neben*, *über*, *unter*, *vor*, *zwischen* which can govern either the accusative or the dative.
[src:bulgarian-language/accusative-case] The latter prepositions take the accusative when motion or action is specified (being done into/onto the space), but take the dative when location is specified (being done in/on that space).
[src:bulgarian-language/accusative-case] These prepositions are also used in conjunction with certain verbs, in which case it is the verb in question which governs whether the accusative or dative should be used.
[src:bulgarian-language/accusative-case] Adjective endings also change in the accusative case.
[src:bulgarian-language/accusative-case] Another factor that determines the endings of adjectives is whether the adjective is being used after a definite article (the), after an indefinite article (a/an) or without any article before the adjective (*many* green apples).
[src:bulgarian-language/accusative-case] In German, the accusative case is also used for some adverbial expressions, mostly temporal ones, as in *Diesen Abend bleibe ich daheim* (This evening I'm staying at home), where *diesen Abend* is marked as accusative, although not a direct object.
[src:bulgarian-language/accusative-case] In Russian, accusative is used not only to display the direct object of an action, but also to indicate the destination or goal of motion.
[src:bulgarian-language/accusative-case] The prepositions в and на can both take accusative in situations where they are indicating the goal of a motion.
[src:bulgarian-language/accusative-case] In the masculine, Russian also distinguishes between animate and inanimate nouns with regard to the accusative; only the animates carry a marker in this case.
[src:bulgarian-language/accusative-case] The PIE accusative case has nearly eroded in Russian, merging with the genitive or the nominative in most declensions.
[src:bulgarian-language/accusative-case] Only singular first-declension nouns (ending in 'а', 'я', or 'ия') have a distinct accusative ('у', 'ю', or 'ию').
[src:bulgarian-language/accusative-case] In Polish, the accusative case has two functions: showing the direct object of an action, and showing the goal of motion.
[src:bulgarian-language/accusative-case] Inanimate masculine nouns in accusative case are usually written the same as in nominative case, whereas animate masculine nouns receive the ending ***-a***.
[src:bulgarian-language/accusative-case] Feminine nouns ending with a consonant are written the same as in nominative case.
[src:bulgarian-language/accusative-case] Neuter nouns are written the same in accusative case as they are in nominative case.
[src:bulgarian-language/accusative-case] The direct object function of the accusative case in Polish is often used with verbs like *mieć* 'to have', *jeść* 'to eat', *pić* 'to drink', *czytać* 'to read' and *lubić* 'to like'.
[src:bulgarian-language/accusative-case] The motion function of the accusative case is used with the prepositions *na*, *o*, *po*, *pod*, *przez(e)*, *w(e)*, and *za*.
[src:bulgarian-language/accusative-case] According to the traditional Finnish grammar, the accusative case is used for a total object, while the partitive case is used for a partial object.
[src:bulgarian-language/accusative-case] The accusative is identical to either the nominative case or the genitive case, except for personal pronouns and the personal interrogative pronoun *kuka*/*ken*, which have a special accusative form ending in *-t*.
[src:bulgarian-language/accusative-case] The major new Finnish grammar, *Iso suomen kielioppi*, deviates from the traditional classification to limit the accusative case to the special case of personal pronouns and *kuka*/*ken*.
[src:bulgarian-language/accusative-case] This grammar considers other total objects as being in the nominative or genitive case.
[src:bulgarian-language/accusative-case] The accusative case is assigned to the direct object in a sentence in Hungarian.
[src:bulgarian-language/accusative-case] The accusative marker is always *-t*, often preceded by a linking vowel to facilitate pronunciation.
[src:bulgarian-language/accusative-case] Every personal pronoun has an accusative form.
[src:bulgarian-language/accusative-case] For the Hungarian 1st and 2nd person singular accusative forms, the pronoun can often be dropped if it is clear from the context who the speaker is referring to.
[src:bulgarian-language/accusative-case] Accusative case marking existed in Proto-Semitic, Akkadian, and Ugaritic.
[src:bulgarian-language/accusative-case] It is preserved today in many Semitic languages as Modern Standard Arabic, Hebrew and Ge'ez.
[src:bulgarian-language/accusative-case] The accusative case is called in Arabic النصب (*an-naṣb*) and it has many other uses in addition to marking the object of a verb.
[src:bulgarian-language/accusative-case] In Hebrew, if the object of the sentence is a pronoun (e.g., I, you, s/he) and the transitive verb requires a direct object, the word אֵת *et* is combined with the pronoun into an object pronoun.
[src:bulgarian-language/accusative-case] In Japanese, cases are marked by placing particles after nouns.
[src:bulgarian-language/accusative-case] The accusative case is marked with を (*wo*, pronounced /o̞/).
[src:bulgarian-language/accusative-case] In Korean, the accusative case is marked with 를 or 을.
[src:bulgarian-language/accusative-case] The postpositions depend on a word's last syllable.
[src:bulgarian-language/accusative-case] In Turkish, cases are marked with suffixes.
[src:bulgarian-language/accusative-case] The accusative case is marked with the suffixes *-ı, -i, -u, -ü*, depending on vowel harmony.
[src:bulgarian-language/accusative-case] If a word ends in a vowel, *-y-* is added before the suffix as a buffer consonant.
[src:bulgarian-language/accusative-case] The accusative is only used if the direct object of a sentence is definite.
[src:bulgarian-language/accusative-case] If it is indefinite, the nominative case is used.
[src:bulgarian-language/accusative-case] In Malayalam, the accusative inflection is achieved using the suffix എ /-e/.
[src:bulgarian-language/accusative-case] The sandhi also play a role here depending on the ending of the noun.
[src:bulgarian-language/accusative-case] Example: മരം /maram/ → മരത്തെ /maratte/ where /tt/ replaces /m/ when /e/ is suffixed.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] In linguistics, a **participle** (from Latin **participium** 'a sharing, partaking'; abbr.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] **ptcp**) is a nonfinite verb form that has some of the characteristics and functions of both verbs and adjectives.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] More narrowly, *participle* has been defined as "a word derived from a verb and used as an adjective, as in a *laughing face*".
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] "Participle" is a traditional grammatical term from Greek and Latin that is widely used for corresponding verb forms in European languages and analogous forms in Sanskrit and Arabic grammar.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] In particular, Greek and Latin participles are inflected for gender, number and case, but also conjugated for tense and voice and can take prepositional and adverbial modifiers.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] Cross-linguistically, participles may have a range of functions apart from adjectival modification.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] In European and Indian languages, the past participle is used to form the passive voice.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] In English, participles are also associated with periphrastic verb forms (continuous and perfect) and are widely used in adverbial clauses.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] In non-Indo-European languages, 'participle' has been applied to forms that are alternatively regarded as converbs (see Sirenik below), gerunds, gerundives, transgressives, and nominalised verbs in complement clauses.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] As a result, 'participles' have come to be associated with a broad variety of syntactic constructions.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] The word *participle* comes from classical Latin *participium*, from *particeps* 'sharing, participation', because it shares certain properties of verbs, adjectives, and adverbs.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] The Latin grammatical term is a calque of the Greek grammatical term μετοχή : *metochē*, 'participation, participle'.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] The linguistic term, *past participle*, was coined circa 1798 based on its participial form, whose morphology equates to the regular form of preterite verbs.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] The term, *present participle*, was first used c.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] 1864 to facilitate grammatical distinctions.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] Despite the taxonomical use of "past" and "present" as associated with the aforementioned participles, their respective semantic use can entail any tense, regardless of aspect, depending on how they are structurally combined.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] **present participle**, which is formed with an *-ing* suffix (e.g.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] Some grammars further distinguish *passive participles* as often associated with passive voice versus *active participles* as often associated with e.g. the present progressive tense, but such linguistic distinctions are neither recognized nor employed on a universal basis.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] Participles can be used adjectivally (i.e. without characteristics of canonical verbs) as *attributive adjectives*.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] Unlike standard verbs, participles don’t typically have objects or the usual modifiers that verbs have.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] However, they can be modified by adverbs such as *very* or *slightly*.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] In the first sentence, *interesting* functions transitively in a non-finite sense as a participle that expresses the object *him*, thereby forming the grammatical equivalent of "[that is] *interesting him*".
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] In the second and third sentences, *interesting* functions as a prepositive adjective modifying *subject*.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] An adverb (such as *very* or *recently*) or a prefix (such as *un-*) can preface adjectival participles: "a *very frightened* rabbit", "*recently fallen* leaves", "*uninterested* people".
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] Some languages differentiate **adjectival participles** and **adverbial participles**.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] An adverbial participle (or a participial phrase/clause based on such a participle) plays the role of an adverbial phrase in the sentence in which it appears, whereas an adjectival participle (or a participial phrase/clause based on one) plays the role of an adjective phrase.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] Such languages include Russian and other Slavic languages, Hungarian, and many Eskimo languages, such as Sirenik, which has a sophisticated participle system.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] Details can be found in the sections below or in the articles on the grammars of specific languages.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] Grammatical descriptions vary in the way these are treated.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] Some descriptive grammars treat such adverbial and adjectival participles as distinct lexical categories, while others include them both in a single category of participles.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] Adverbial participles in certain languages may be called converbs, gerunds, or gerundives (though this is not consistent with the meanings of the terms *gerund* or *gerundive* as normally applied to English or Latin), or transgressives.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] Participles are often used to form certain grammatical tenses or grammatical aspects.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] The two types of participle in Modern English are termed **present participle** and **past participle**, respectively (often also referred to as the *-ing form* and *-ed/-en form*).
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] The traditional terms are misleading because the participles do not necessarily correspond to tense: the present participle is often associated with the progressive (continuous) aspect, while the past participle is linked with the perfect aspect or passive voice.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] The first sentence is in the past tense (*were*), but a present participle expresses the progressive aspect (*be standing*).
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] The second sentence is in the future tense (*will*), but a past participle is used for the perfect aspect (*have cleaned*).
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] Participles may also be identified with a particular voice: active or passive.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] Some languages (such as Latin and Russian) have distinct participles for active and passive uses.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] In English, the present participle is essentially an active participle, and the past participle has both active and passive uses.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] In Old English, past participles of Germanic strong verbs were marked with a *ġe-* prefix, a West Germanic feature still found in most strong and weak past participles in Dutch and German today, and often by a vowel change in the stem.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] Those of weak verbs were marked by the ending *-d*, with or without an epenthetic vowel before it.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] Modern English past participles derive from these forms (although the *ġe-* prefix, which became *y-* in Middle English, has now been lost — except in some rare dialects such as the Dorset dialect, where it takes the form of *a-*).
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] Old English present participles were marked with an ending in *-ende* (or *-iende* for verbs whose infinitives ended in *-ian*).
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] In Middle English, the form of the present participle varied across regions: *-ende* (southwest, southeast, Midlands), *-inde* (southwest, southeast), *-and* (north), *-inge* (southeast).
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] The last is the one that became standard, falling together with the suffix *-ing* used to form verbal nouns.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] In addition, various compound participles can be formed, such as *having done*, *being done*, *having been doing*, *having been done*.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] Details of participle formation can be found under English verbs and List of English irregular verbs.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] Additionally, participles that express an adjectivally attributive meaning can be affixed to form adverbs, such as *interestingly* and *excitedly*.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] Note that a past participle that complements a stative verb (e.g., "The files that *are attached* or "Our comrades who *have fallen*") becomes a passive participle within a passive voice construct.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] The gerund is traditionally regarded as distinct from the present participle.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] A gerund can function transitively (e.g., "I like *eating ice cream*") or intransitively (e.g., "I like *swimming*").
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] In both instances, a gerund functions nominatively rather than adjectivally or adverbially—whether as an object (e.g., "I like *sleeping*") or as a subject (e.g., "*Sleeping* is not allowed").
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] Although *gerunds* and *present participles* are morphologically identical, their grammatical functions differ substantially.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] When the meaning is "The practice of flying a plane is dangerous," *flying* functions as a gerund; when the danger concerns "Planes that fly" or "Planes when they are flying" (i.e., in contrast to *grounded planes*), *flying* is being used adjectivally as a participle.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] For more on the distinctions between these uses of the *-ing* verb form, see *-ing*: uses.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] For more details on uses of participles and other parts of verbs in English, see Uses of English verb forms, including the sections on the present participle and past participle.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] In all of the Scandinavian languages the past participle has to agree with the noun to some degree.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] All of the Scandinavian languages have mandatory agreement with the noun in number.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] Nynorsk and Swedish have mandatory agreement in both number and gender.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] Icelandic and Faroese have agreement in number, gender and case.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] The verb form used for the perfect (or "supine") aspect is generally identical to the nominative neuter singular form of the past participle for all verbs.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] For the present participle there is no agreement.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] The first example involves a present participle and the two latter examples involves a past participle.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] All present participles end with an -ande suffix.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] In Norwegian, the present participle may be used to form adjectives or adverbs denoting the possibility or convenience of performing the action prescribed by the verb.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] This construction is allowed in Nynorsk, but not in Bokmål, where suffixes like *-elig* or *-bar* are used instead.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] Latin grammar was studied in Europe for hundreds of years, especially the handbook written by the 4th-century teacher Aelius Donatus, and it is from Latin that the name and concept of the participle derives.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] However, many modern Latin grammars treat the gerundive as a separate part of speech.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] The perfect participle is usually passive in meaning, and thus mainly formed from transitive verbs, for example *frāctus* "broken", *missus* "sent (by someone)".
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] However, certain verbs (called deponent verbs) have a perfect participle in an active sense, e.g.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] *profectus* "having set out", *hortātus* "having encouraged", etc.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] The present and future participles are always active, the gerundive usually passive.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] Because a participle is an adjective as well as a verb, just like any other Latin adjective its ending changes according to the noun it describes.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] So when the noun is masculine, the participle must be masculine; when the noun is in the accusative (object) case, the participle is also in the accusative case; when the noun has plural endings, the participle also has plural endings.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] Thus a simple participle such as *frāctus* "broken" can change to *frācta*, *frāctum*, *frāctī*, *frāctō* and so on, according to its gender, number, and case.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] A participle can have a descriptive meaning like an adjective, or a more dynamic meaning like a verb.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] The dynamic, verbal meaning is more common, and Latin often uses a participle where English might use a simple verb.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] The present participle often describes the circumstances attending the main verb.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] For uses of the gerundive, see Latin syntax § The gerundive.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] *amante* "loving" or "lover", *viviente* "living" or "live".
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] The past participle (*participio pasado* or *participio pasivo*) is regularly formed with one of the suffixes *-ado* or *-ido* (*-ado* for verbs ending in *-ar* and *-ido* for verbs ending in *-er* or *-ir*; but some verbs have an irregular form ending in *-to* (e.g.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] The past participle is used generally as an adjective referring to a finished action, in which case its ending changes according to gender and number.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] At other times is used to form compound tenses: the present perfect, past perfect (sometimes referred to as the *pluscuamperfecto*), and the future perfect, in which case it is indeclinable.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] The Ancient Greek participle shares in the properties of adjectives and verbs.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] Like an adjective, it changes form for gender, case, and number.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] Like a verb, it has tense and voice, is modified by adverbs, and can take verb arguments, including an object.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] Participles are quite numerous in Ancient Greek: a non-defective verb has as many as ten participles.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] There is a form of the participle for every combination of aspect (present, aorist, perfect, future) and voice (active, middle, passive).
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] All participles are based on their finite forms.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] Like an adjective, it can modify a noun, and can be used to embed one thought into another.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] In the example, the participial phrase τὸν εὖ στρατηγήσοντα *tòn eû stratēgḗsonta*, literally "the one going to be a good general", is used to embed the idea εὖ στρατηγήσει *eû stratēgḗsei* "he will be a good general" within the main verb.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] The participle is very widely used in Ancient Greek, especially in prose.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] There are two types of participles in Hindi and Urdu (called together Hindustani), aspectual participles which mark the aspect and non-aspectual participles which do not mark verbal aspect.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] The table below mentions the different participles present in Hindustani, *ɸ* denotes the verb root.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] The aspectual participles can take a few other copulas after them besides the verb *honā* "to be".
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] Those copular verbs are *rêhna* "to stay", *ānā* "to come", *jānā* "to go".
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] Much like Ancient Greek, Sanskrit has a wide array of participles.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] In Cornish, an equivalent present participle construction to English is formed by using *ow* (*owth* before vowels) with a verbal noun, e.g.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] *Yma an den ow hwerthin* ("The man is laughing"), and *den ow hwerthin* ("a laughing man").
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] Like Breton but unlike Welsh, Cornish also has verbal adjectives which are used similarly to English past participles, e.g.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] *dehen molys* ("clotted cream"), from the verbal noun *mola* "to clot".
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] In Welsh, the effect of a participle in the active voice is constructed by *yn* followed by the verb-noun (for the present participle) and *wedi* followed by the verb-noun (for the past participle).
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] In the passive voice, participles are usually replaced by a compound phrase such as *wedi cael ei/eu* ("having got his/her/their ...ing") in modern Welsh and by the impersonal form in literary Welsh.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] The Polish word for participle is *imiesłów* (pl.: *imiesłowy*).
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] Due to the distinction between adjectival and adverbial participles, in Polish it is practically impossible to make a dangling participle in the classical English meaning of the term.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] it is unclear whether "I" or "they" were hiding in the closet.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] Future participles formed from perfective verbs are not considered a part of standard language.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] Participles are adjectives formed from verbs.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] Macedonian has completely lost or transformed the participles of Common Slavic, unlike the other Slavic languages.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] Among Indo-European languages, the Lithuanian language is unique for having 14 different participial forms of the verb, which can be grouped into five when accounting for inflection by tense.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] Some of these are also inflected by gender and case.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] The active and passive participles and the semi-participles are inflected by gender, and the active, passive and necessity participles are inflected by case.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] The Arabic verb has two participles: an active participle (*ʾism al-fāʿil* اسم الفاعل) and a passive participle (*ʾism al-mafʿūl* اسم المفعول), and the form of the participle is predictable by inspection of the dictionary form of the verb.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] These participles are inflected for gender, number and case, but not person.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] Arabic participles are employed syntactically in a variety of ways: as nouns, as adjectives or even as verbs.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] Their uses vary across varieties of Arabic.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] In general the active participle describes a property of the syntactic subject of the verb from which it derives, whilst the passive participles describes the object.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] For example, from the verb كتب *kataba*, the active participle is *kātib* كاتب and the passive participle is *maktūb* مكتوب.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] Roughly these translate to "writing" and "written" respectively.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] However, they have different, derived lexical uses. كاتب *kātib* is further lexicalized as "writer", "author" and مكتوب *maktūb* as "letter".
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] In Classical Arabic, the participles do not participate in verbal constructions with auxiliaries the same way as their English counterparts and rarely take on a verbal meaning in a sentence (a notable exception being participles derived from motion verbs as well as participles in Qur'anic Arabic).
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] In certain dialects of Arabic, however, it is much more common for the participles, especially the active participle, to have verbal force in the sentence.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] For example, in dialects of the Levant, the active participle is a structure that describes the state of the syntactic subject after the action of the verb from which it derives has taken place.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] *ʼĀkil*, the active participle of *ʼakala* ("to eat"), describes one's state after having eaten something.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] Therefore, it can be used in analogous way to the English present perfect (for example, *ʼAnā ʼākil* انا آكل meaning "I have eaten", "I have just eaten" or "I have already eaten").
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] Other verbs, such as *rāḥa* راح ("to go") give a participle (*rāyiḥ* رايح), which has a progressive ("is going…") meaning.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] The exact tense or continuity of the participles is, therefore, determined by the nature of the specific verb (especially its lexical aspect and its transitivity) and the syntactic/semantic context of the utterance.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] What ties them all together is that they describe the subject of the verb from which they derive.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] The passive participles in certain dialects can be used as a sort of passive voice, but more often than not, they are used in their various lexicalized senses as adjectives or nouns.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] Like Arabic, Hebrew has two types of participles (בינוני *bênônî*): an active participle (בינוני פועל *bênônî pô'ēl*) and a passive participle (בינוני פעול *bênônî pā'ûl*).
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] These participles are inflected for gender and number.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] The active participle takes a variety of syntactic roles, such as a verb in present tense, a noun, and an adjective.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] Hebrew has a syntactic construction of the verb "to be" (הָיָה, *hayá*) in the past tense, and the active participle that cognates to the past progressive tense in English.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] For example, the word עבדתי *avádti* means "I worked", and הייתי עובד *hayíti ovéd* means "I was working".
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] Another use of this syntactic structure is equivalent to "used to" in English.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] For example, דויד בילדותו היה גר בארצות הברית *davíd b'yaldutó hayá gar b'arcót habrít* (David in his childhood used to live in the United States).
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] Finnish uses six participles (*partisiippi*) to convey different meanings.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] Below is a table displaying the declension of the participles of the verb *tappaa* (to kill).
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] Each of the participles can be used as adjectives and so some of them can be turned into nouns.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] Hungarian uses adjectival and adverbial participles.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] In Hungarian grammar, the infinitive is also considered a kind of participle, the noun participle (*főnévi igenév*).
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] Participles are called *sıfat-fiil* (lit.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] 'adjective-verb') or *ortaç* in Turkish.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] Turkish participles consist of a verb stem and a suffix.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] Some participles may be conjugated, but some may not.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] Participles always precede the noun they are defining, unlike in English.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] Participle suffixes, like many other suffixes in Turkish, change according to the vowel harmony and sandhi.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] A mnemonic for the eight types is taught in Turkish schools: *Anası mezar dikecekmiş*, which includes the sound of each participial suffix in a coherent sentence meaning "his/her mother is allegedly going to plant (i.e. erect) a grave(stone)".
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] Sirenik language, an extinct Eskimo–Aleut language, had separate sets of *adverbial participles* and *adjectival participles*.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] Unlike in English, adverbial participles were conjugated to reflect the person and number of their implicit subjects; hence, an adverbial participle could replace a clause in the English sentence "If *I* were a marksman, *I* would kill walruses" since the subject was implied by the conjugation.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] Esperanto has six different participle conjugations; active and passive for past, present and future.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] For example, a *falonta botelo* is a bottle that will fall or is about to fall.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] A *falanta botelo* is one that is falling through the air.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] After it hits the floor, it is a *falinta botelo*.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] These examples use the active participles, but the usage of the passive participles is similar.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] A cake that is going to be divided is a *dividota kuko*.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] When it is in the process of being divided, it is a *dividata kuko*.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] Having been cut, it is now a *dividita kuko*.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] These participles can be used in conjunction with the verb to be, *esti*, forming 18 compound tenses (9 active and 9 passive).
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] However, this soon becomes complicated and often unnecessary, and is only frequently used when rigorous translation of English is required.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] An example of this would be *la knabo estos instruita*, or, 'the boy will have been taught'.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] This example sentence is then in the future anterior.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] When the suffix *-o* is used, instead of *-a*, then the participle refers to a person.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] Also, a *manĝito* is someone who was eaten, a *manĝato* is someone who is being eaten, and a *manĝoto* is someone who will be eaten.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] These rules hold true for all transitive verbs.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] Since copular and intransitive verbs do not have passive voice, their participle forms can only be active.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] An informal and unofficial addition to these six are the participles for conditional forms, which use *-unt-* and *-ut-*.
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] For example, *parolunto* refers to someone who would speak (or would have spoken), and a *leguta libro* is a book that would be read (or have been read).
[src:bulgarian-language/adverbial-participle] These unofficial participle forms are however very rarely used in practice.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] The **Aegean Sea** is an elongated embayment of the Mediterranean Sea between Europe and Asia.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] It is located between the Balkans and Anatolia, and covers an area of some 215,000 km2 (83,000 sq mi).
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] In the north, the Aegean is connected to the Marmara Sea, which in turn connects to the Black Sea, by the straits of the Dardanelles and the Bosphorus, respectively.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] The Aegean Islands are located within the sea and some bound it on its southern periphery, including Crete and Rhodes.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] The sea reaches a maximum depth of 2,639 m (8,658 ft) to the west of Karpathos.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] The Thracian Sea and the Sea of Crete are main subdivisions of the Aegean Sea.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] The Aegean Islands can be divided into several island groups, including the Dodecanese, the Cyclades, the Sporades, the Saronic islands and the North Aegean Islands, as well as Crete and its surrounding islands.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] The Dodecanese, located to the southeast, includes the islands of Rhodes, Kos, and Patmos; the islands of Delos and Naxos are within the Cyclades to the south of the sea.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] Lesbos is part of the North Aegean Islands.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] Euboea, the second-largest island in Greece, is located in the Aegean, despite being administered as part of Central Greece.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] Nine out of twelve of the Administrative regions of Greece border the sea, along with the Turkish provinces of Edirne, Çanakkale, Balıkesir, İzmir, Aydın and Muğla to the east of the sea.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] Various Turkish islands in the sea are Imbros, Tenedos, Cunda Island, and the Foça Islands.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] The Aegean Sea has been historically important, especially regarding the civilization of Ancient Greece, which inhabited the area around the coast of the Aegean and the Aegean islands.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] The Aegean islands facilitated contact between the people of the area and between Europe and Asia.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] Along with the Greeks, Thracians lived along the northern coasts.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] The Romans conquered the area under the Roman Empire, and later the Byzantine Empire held it against advances by the First Bulgarian Empire.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] The Fourth Crusade weakened Byzantine control of the area, and it was eventually conquered by the Ottoman Empire, with the exception of Crete, which was a Venetian colony until 1669.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] The Greek War of Independence allowed a Greek state on the coast of the Aegean from 1829 onwards.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] The Ottoman Empire held a presence over the sea for over 500 years until it was replaced by modern Turkey.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] The rocks making up the floor of the Aegean are mainly limestone, though often greatly altered by volcanic activity that has convulsed the region in relatively recent geologic times.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] Of particular interest are the richly colored sediments in the region of the islands of Santorini and Milos, in the south Aegean.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] Notable cities on the Aegean coastline include Athens, Thessaloniki, Heraklion, Volos, Alexandroupolis and Kavala in Greece, and İzmir and Bodrum in Turkey.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] Several issues concerning sovereignty within the Aegean Sea are disputed between Greece and Turkey.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] The Aegean dispute has had a large effect on Greece-Turkey relations since the 1970s.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] Issues include the delimitation of territorial waters, national airspace, exclusive economic zones, and flight information regions.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] Ancient Greek authors also called it the "Greek Sea".
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] The sea was known in Latin as *Mare Aegaeum* while under the control of the Roman Empire.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] Pliny the Elder write that the Romans used the terms "Macedonian" for the northern part near Macedonia and Thrace provinces, and "Grecian" for the part near Greece itself.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] In medieval Latin, the Aegean Sea was known as *Egeopelagus*, a form attested as late as 1419 in Venetian state papers (Ducatus Egeopelagi) and derived from the Greek αἰγαιοπέλαγος / αἰγαῖον πέλαγος.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] The term *Arcipelago* also appears, for instance in a treaty on 30 June 1268 between the Venetians and the emperor Michael Palaeologus.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] This term subsequently gave rise to *Archipelago* (Greek: αρχιπέλαγος), which in many European languages originally referred specifically to the Aegean Sea.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] The terms *Greek Archipelago* or *Grecian Archipelago* were also used.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] Later, as archipelago came to be used increasingly as a generic term for island-studded seas, the terms Greek Archipelago or Grecian Archipelago continued to be used alongside the ancient name, Aegean Sea.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] In some South Slavic languages, the Aegean is called *White Sea* (Bulgarian: Бяло море, romanized: *Byalo more*; Macedonian: Бело море, romanized: *Belo more*; Serbian: *Belo more* / Бело море).
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] The Turkish name for the sea is *Ege Denizi*, which is derived from the Greek name, and *Adalar Denizi* meaning "Sea of Islands".
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] In the past, Turks also referred to it as the "White Sea", to differentiate it from the Black Sea.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] The Aegean Sea is an elongated embayment of the Mediterranean Sea and covers about 214,000 square kilometres (83,000 sq mi) in area, measuring about 670 kilometres (420 mi) longitudinally and 390 kilometres (240 mi) latitudinal.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] The sea's maximum depth is 2,639 metres (8,658 ft), located at a point west of Karpathos.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] The Aegean Islands are found within its waters, with the following islands delimiting the sea on the south, generally from west to east: Kythera, Antikythera, Crete, Kasos, Karpathos and Rhodes.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] The Anatolian peninsula marks the eastern boundary of the sea, while the Greek mainland marks the west.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] Several seas are contained within the Aegean Sea; the Thracian Sea is a section of the Aegean located to the north, the Icarian Sea to the east, the Myrtoan Sea to the west, while the Sea of Crete is the southern section.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] The Greek regions that border the sea, in alphabetical order, are Attica, Central Greece, Central Macedonia, Crete, Eastern Macedonia and Thrace, North Aegean, Peloponnese, South Aegean, and Thessaly.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] The traditional Greek region of Macedonia also borders the sea, to the north.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] Many of the Aegean islands or island chains, are geographical extensions of the mountains on the mainland.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] One chain extends across the sea to Chios, another extends across Euboea to Samos, and a third extends across the Peloponnese and Crete to Rhodes, dividing the Aegean from the Mediterranean.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] The Aegean Sea is connected to the Sea of Marmara by the Dardanelles, also known from Classical Antiquity as the Hellespont.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] The Dardanelles are located to the northeast of the sea.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] It ultimately connects with the Black Sea through the Bosporus strait, upon which lies the city of Istanbul.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] The Dardanelles and the Bosporus are known as the Turkish Straits.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] Aegean surface water circulates in a counterclockwise gyre, with hypersaline Mediterranean water moving northward along the west coast of Turkey, before being displaced by less dense Black Sea outflow.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] The dense Mediterranean water sinks below the Black Sea inflow to a depth of 23–30 metres (75–98 ft), then flows through the Dardanelles Strait and into the Sea of Marmara at velocities of 5–15 cm/s (2–6 in/s).
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] The Black Sea outflow moves westward along the northern Aegean Sea, then flows southwards along the east coast of Greece.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] The physical oceanography of the Aegean Sea is controlled mainly by the regional climate, the fresh water discharge from major rivers draining southeastern Europe, and the seasonal variations in the Black Sea surface water outflow through the Dardanelles Strait.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] The climate of the Aegean Sea largely reflects the climate of Greece and Western Turkey, which is to say, predominantly Mediterranean.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] According to the Köppen climate classification, most of the Aegean is classified as Hot-summer Mediterranean (*Csa*), with hotter and drier summers along with milder and wetter winters.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] However, high temperatures during summers are generally not quite as high as those in arid or semiarid climates due to the presence of a large body of water.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] This is most predominant in the west and east coasts of the Aegean, and within the Aegean islands.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] In the north of the Aegean Sea, the climate is instead classified as Cold semi-arid *(BSk)*, which feature cooler summers than Hot-summer Mediterranean climates.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] The Etesian winds are a dominant weather influence in the Aegean Basin.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] Numerous Greek and Turkish settlements are located along their mainland coast, as well as on towns on the Aegean islands.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] The largest cities are Athens and Thessaloniki in Greece and İzmir in Turkey.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] The most populated of the Aegean islands is Crete, followed by Euboea and Rhodes.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] Greece has established several marine protected areas along its coasts.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] According to the Network of Managers of Marine Protected Areas in the Mediterranean (MedPAN), four Greek MPAs are participating in the Network.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] These include Alonnisos Marine Park, while the Missolonghi–Aitoliko Lagoons and the island of Zakynthos are not on the Aegean.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] The current coastline dates back to about 4000 BC.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] Before that time, at the peak of the last ice age (about 18,000 years ago) sea levels everywhere were 130 metres (430 ft) lower, and there were large well-watered coastal plains instead of much of the northern Aegean.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] When they were first occupied, the present-day islands including Milos with its important obsidian production were probably still connected to the mainland.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] The present coastal arrangement appeared around 9,000 years ago, with post-ice age sea levels continuing to rise for another 3,000 years after that.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] The subsequent Bronze Age civilizations of Greece and the Aegean Sea have given rise to the general term *Aegean civilization*.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] In ancient times, the sea was the birthplace of two ancient civilizations – the Minoans of Crete and the Mycenaeans of the Peloponnese.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] The Minoan civilization was a Bronze Age civilization on the island of Crete and other Aegean islands, flourishing from around 3000 to 1450 BC before a period of decline, finally ending at around 1100 BC.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] It represented the first advanced civilization in Europe, leaving behind massive building complexes, tools, stunning artwork, writing systems, and a massive network of trade.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] The Minoan period saw extensive trade between Crete, Aegean, and Mediterranean settlements, particularly the Near East.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] The most notable Minoan palace is that of Knossos, followed by that of Phaistos.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] The Mycenaean Greeks arose on the mainland, becoming the first advanced civilization in mainland Greece, which lasted from approximately 1600 to 1100 BC.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] It is believed that the site of Mycenae, which sits close to the Aegean coast, was the center of Mycenaean civilization.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] The Mycenaeans introduced several innovations in the fields of engineering, architecture and military infrastructure, while trade over vast areas of the Mediterranean, including the Aegean, was essential for the Mycenaean economy.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] Their syllabic script, the Linear B, offers the first written records of the Greek language and their religion already included several deities that can also be found in the Olympic Pantheon.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] Mycenaean Greece was dominated by a warrior elite society and consisted of a network of palace-centered states that developed rigid hierarchical, political, social and economic systems.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] At the head of this society was the king, known as *wanax*.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] The civilization of Mycenaean Greeks perished with the collapse of Bronze Age culture in the eastern Mediterranean, to be followed by the so-called Greek Dark Ages.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] It is undetermined what cause the collapse of the Mycenaeans.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] During the Greek Dark Ages, writing in the Linear B script ceased, vital trade links were lost, and towns and villages were abandoned.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] The Archaic period followed the Greek Dark Ages in the 8th century BC.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] Greece became divided into small self-governing communities, and adopted the Phoenician alphabet, modifying it to create the Greek alphabet.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] By the 6th century BC several cities had emerged as dominant in Greek affairs: Athens, Sparta, Corinth, and Thebes, of which Athens, Sparta, and Corinth were closest to the Aegean Sea.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] Each of them had brought the surrounding rural areas and smaller towns under their control, and Athens and Corinth had become major maritime and mercantile powers as well.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] In the 8th and 7th centuries BC many Greeks migrated to form colonies in Magna Graecia (Southern Italy and Sicily), Asia Minor and further afield.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] The Aegean Sea was the setting for one of the most pivotal naval engagements in history, when, on 20 September 480 B.C., the Athenian fleet gained a decisive victory over the Persian fleet of the Xerxes II of Persia at the Battle of Salamis.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] Thus ending any further attempt of western expansion by the Achaemenid Empire.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] The Aegean Sea would later come to be under the control, albeit briefly, of the Kingdom of Macedonia.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] Philip II and his son Alexander the Great led a series of conquests that led not only to the unification of the Greek mainland and the control of the Aegean Sea under his rule, but also the destruction of the Achaemenid Empire.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] After Alexander the Great's death, his empire was divided among his generals.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] Cassander became king of the Hellenistic kingdom of Macedon, which held territory along the western coast of the Aegean, roughly corresponding to modern-day Greece.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] The Kingdom of Lysimachus had control over the sea's eastern coast.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] Greece had entered the Hellenistic period.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] The Macedonian Wars were a series of conflicts fought by the Roman Republic and its Greek allies in the eastern Mediterranean against several different major Greek kingdoms.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] They resulted in Roman control or influence over the eastern Mediterranean basin, including the Aegean, in addition to their hegemony in the western Mediterranean after the Punic Wars.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] During Roman rule, the land around the Aegean Sea fell under the provinces of Achaea, Macedonia, Thracia, Asia and Creta et Cyrenaica (island of Crete).
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] The fall of the Western Roman Empire allowed its successor state, the Byzantine Empire, to continue Roman control over the Aegean Sea.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] However, their territory would later be threatened by the early Muslim conquests initiated by Muhammad in the 7th century.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] Although the Rashidun Caliphate did not manage to obtain land along the coast of the Aegean Sea, its conquest of the Eastern Anatolian peninsula as well as Egypt, the Levant, and North Africa left the Byzantine Empire weakened.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] The Umayyad Caliphate expanded the territorial gains of the Rashidun Caliphate, conquering much of North Africa, and threatened the Byzantine Empire's control of Western Anatolia, where it meets the Aegean Sea.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] During the 820s, Crete was conquered by a group of Berbers Andalusians exiles led by Abu Hafs Umar al-Iqritishi, and it became an independent Islamic state.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] The Byzantine Empire launched a campaign that took most of the island back in 842 and 843 under Theoktistos, but the re-conquest was not completed and was soon reversed.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] Later attempts by the Byzantine Empire to recover the island were without success.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] For the approximately 135 years of its existence, the emirate of Crete was one of the major foes of Byzantium.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] Crete commanded the sea lanes of the Eastern Mediterranean and functioned as a forward base and haven for Muslim corsair fleets that ravaged the Byzantine-controlled shores of the Aegean Sea.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] Crete returned to Byzantine rule under Nikephoros II Phokas, who launched a huge campaign against the Emirate of Crete in 960 to 961.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] Meanwhile, the Bulgarian Empire threatened Byzantine control of Northern Greece and the Aegean coast to the south.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] Under Presian and his successor Boris I, the Bulgarian Empire managed to obtain a small portion of the northern Aegean coast.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] Simeon I of Bulgaria led Bulgaria to its greatest territorial expansion, and managed to conqueror much of the northern and western coasts of the Aegean.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] The Second Bulgarian Empire achieved similar success along, again, the northern and western coasts, under Ivan Asen II of Bulgaria.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] The Seljuk Turks, under the Seljuk Empire, invaded the Byzantine Empire in 1068, from which they annexed almost all the territories of Anatolia, including the east coast of the Aegean Sea, during the reign of Alp Arslan, the second Sultan of the Seljuk Empire.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] After the death of his successor, Malik Shah I, the empire was divided, and Malik Shah was succeeded in Anatolia by Kilij Arslan I, who founded the Sultanate of Rum.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] The Byzantines yet again recaptured the eastern coast of the Aegean.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] The Venetians created the maritime state of the Duchy of the Archipelago, which included all the Cyclades except Mykonos and Tinos.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] The Empire of Nicaea, a Byzantine rump state, managed to affect the Recapture of Constantinople from the Latins in 1261 and defeat Epirus.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] Byzantine successes were not to last; the Ottomans would conquer the area around the Aegean coast, but before their expansion the Byzantine Empire had already been weakened from internal conflict.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] By the late 14th century, the Byzantine Empire had lost all control of the coast of the Aegean Sea and could only exercise power around their capital, Constantinople.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] The Ottoman Empire then gained control of all the Aegean coast with the exception of Crete, which was a Venetian colony until 1669.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] The Greek War of Independence allowed a Greek state on the coast of the Aegean from 1829 onward.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] In the aftermath of the Balkan Wars (1912–1913) Greece expanded northwards along the coast, while Bulgaria gained access in the northernmost section of the sea.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] The Ottoman Empire held a presence over the sea for over 500 years until its dissolution following World War I, when it was replaced by modern Turkey.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] After the war, Greece gained control over the area around the northern coast of the Aegean, including the territory held by Bulgaria.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] By the 1920s, Greece and Turkey had about resumed their present-day borders.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] In the Italo-Turkish War of 1912, Italy captured the Dodecanese islands, and had occupied them since, reneging on the 1919 Venizelos–Tittoni agreement to cede them to Greece.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] The Greco-Italian War took place from October 1940 to April 1941 as part of the Balkans Campaign of World War II.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] The Italian war aim was to establish a Greek puppet state, which would permit the Italian annexation of the Sporades and Cyclades islands in the Aegean Sea, to be administered as a part of the Italian Aegean Islands.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] The German invasion resulted in the Axis occupation of Greece.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] The German troops evacuated Athens on 12 October 1944, and by the end of the month, they had withdrawn from mainland Greece.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] Greece was then liberated by Allied troops.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] Many of the islands in the Aegean have safe harbours and bays.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] In ancient times, navigation through the sea was easier than travelling across the rough terrain of the Greek mainland, and to some extent, the coastal areas of Anatolia.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] Many of the islands are volcanic, and marble and iron are mined on other islands.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] The larger islands have some fertile valleys and plains.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] Of the main islands in the Aegean Sea, two belong to Turkey – Bozcaada (Tenedos) and Gökçeada (Imbros); the rest belong to Greece.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] Between the two countries, there are political disputes over several aspects of political control over the Aegean space, including the size of territorial waters, air control and the delimitation of economic rights to the continental shelf.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] These issues are known as the Aegean dispute.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] Multiple ports are located along the Greek and Turkish coasts of the Aegean Sea.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] The port of Piraeus in Athens is the chief port in Greece, the largest passenger port in Europe and the third largest in the world, servicing about 20 million passengers annually.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] With a throughput of 1.4 million TEUs, Piraeus is placed among the top ten ports in container traffic in Europe and the top container port in the Eastern Mediterranean.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] Piraeus is also the commercial hub of Greek shipping.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] Piraeus bi-annually acts as the focus for a major shipping convention, known as Posidonia, which attracts maritime industry professionals from all over the world.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] Piraeus is currently Greece's third-busiest port in terms of tons of goods transported, behind Agioi Theodoroi and Thessaloniki.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] The central port serves ferry routes to almost every island in the eastern portion of Greece, the island of Crete, the Cyclades, the Dodecanese, and much of the northern and the eastern Aegean Sea, while the western part of the port is used for cargo services.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] As of 2007, the Port of Thessaloniki was the second-largest container port in Greece after the port of Piraeus, making it one of the busiest ports in Greece.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] In 2007, the Port of Thessaloniki handled 14,373,245 tonnes of cargo and 222,824 TEU's.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] Paloukia, on the island of Salamis, is a major passenger port.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] Fish are Greece's second-largest agricultural export, and Greece has Europe's largest fishing fleet.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] Fish captured include sardines, mackerel, grouper, grey mullets, sea bass, and seabream.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] There is a considerable difference between fish catches between the pelagic and demersal zones; with respect to pelagic fisheries, the catches from the northern, central and southern Aegean area groupings are dominated, respectively, by anchovy, horse mackerels, and boops.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] For demersal fisheries, the catches from the northern and southern Aegean area groupings are dominated by grey mullets and pickerel (*Spicara smaris*) respectively.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] The industry has been impacted by the Great Recession.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] Overfishing and habitat destruction is also a concern, threatening grouper, and seabream populations, resulting in perhaps a 50% decline of fish catch.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] To address these concerns, Greek fishermen have been offered a compensation by the government.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] Although some species are defined as protected or threatened under EU legislation, several illegal species such as the molluscs *Pinna nobilis*, *Charonia tritonis* and *Lithophaga lithophaga*, can be bought in restaurants and fish markets around Greece.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] The Aegean islands within the Aegean Sea are significant tourist destinations.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] Tourism to the Aegean islands contributes a significant portion of tourism in Greece, especially since the second half of the 20th century.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] A total of five UNESCO World Heritage sites are located the Aegean Islands; these include the Monastery of Saint John the Theologian and the Cave of the Apocalypse on Patmos, the Pythagoreion and Heraion of Samos in Samos, the Nea Moni of Chios, the island of Delos, and the Medieval City of Rhodes.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] Greece is one of the most visited countries in Europe and the world with over 33 million visitors in 2018, and the tourism industry around a quarter of Greece's Gross Domestic Product.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] The islands of Santorini, Crete, Lesbos, Delos, and Mykonos are common tourist destinations.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] An estimated 2 million tourists visit Santorini annually.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] However, concerns relating to overtourism have arisen in recent years, such as issues of inadequate infrastructure and overcrowding.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] Alongside Greece, Turkey has also been successful in developing resort areas and attracting large number of tourists, contributing to tourism in Turkey.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] The phrase "Blue Cruise" refers to recreational voyages along the Turkish Riviera, including across the Aegean.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] The ancient city of Troy, a World Heritage Site, is on the Turkish coast of the Aegean.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] Greece and Turkey both take part in the Blue Flag beach certification programme of the Foundation for Environmental Education.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] The certification is awarded for beaches and marinas meeting strict quality standards including environmental protection, water quality, safety and services criteria.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] As of 2015, the Blue Flag has been awarded to 395 beaches and 9 marinas in Greece.
[src:bulgarian-language/aegean-sea] Southern Aegean beaches on the Turkish coast include Muğla, with 102 beaches awarded with the blue flag, along with İzmir and Aydın, who have 49 and 30 beaches awarded respectively.
[src:bulgarian-language/agent-grammar] In linguistics, a **grammatical agent** is the thematic relation of the cause or initiator to an event.
[src:bulgarian-language/agent-grammar] The agent is a semantic concept distinct from the subject of a sentence as well as from the topic.
[src:bulgarian-language/agent-grammar] While the subject is determined syntactically, primarily through word order, the agent is determined through its relationship to the action expressed by the verb.
[src:bulgarian-language/agent-grammar] For example, in the sentence "The little girl was bitten by the dog", *girl* is the subject, but *dog* is the agent.
[src:bulgarian-language/agent-grammar] The word *agent* comes from the present participle *agens*, *agentis* ('the one doing') of the Latin verb *agere*, to 'do' or 'make'.
[src:bulgarian-language/agent-grammar] Typically, the situation is denoted by a sentence, the action by a verb in the sentence, and the agent by a noun phrase.
[src:bulgarian-language/agent-grammar] For example, in the sentence "Jack kicked the ball", *Jack* is the agent and *the ball* is the patient.
[src:bulgarian-language/agent-grammar] In certain languages, the agent is declined or otherwise marked to indicate its grammatical role.
[src:bulgarian-language/agent-grammar] Modern English does not mark the agentive grammatical role of a noun in a sentence.
[src:bulgarian-language/agent-grammar] Although certain nouns do have a permanent trait of agency (runner, kicker, etc.), an agent noun is not necessarily an agent of a sentence: "Jack kicked the runner".
[src:bulgarian-language/agent-grammar] For many people, the notion of agency is easy to grasp intuitively but difficult to define: typical qualities that a grammatical agent often has are that it has volition, is sentient or perceives, causes a change of state, or moves.
[src:bulgarian-language/agent-grammar] The linguist David Dowty included these qualities in his definition of a Proto-Agent, and proposed that the nominal with the most elements of the Proto-Agent and the fewest elements of the Proto-Patient tends to be treated as the agent in a sentence.
[src:bulgarian-language/agent-grammar] This solves problems that most semanticists have with deciding on the number and quality of thematic roles.
[src:bulgarian-language/agent-grammar] For example, in the sentence *His energy surprised everyone*, *His energy* is the agent, even though it does not have most of the typical agent-like qualities such as perception, movement, or volition.
[src:bulgarian-language/agent-grammar] (1) April precedes May. vs: (2) May follows April.
[src:bulgarian-language/agent-grammar] Here what is agent and what is patient must be specified for each individual verb.
[src:bulgarian-language/agent-grammar] The grammatical agent is often confused with the subject, but the two notions are quite distinct: the *agent* is based explicitly on its relationship to the action or event expressed by the verb (e.g.
[src:bulgarian-language/agent-grammar] "He who kicked the ball"), whereas the *subject* is based on a more *formal title* using the theory of the information flow (e.g.
[src:bulgarian-language/agent-grammar] In the sentence "The boy kicked the ball", *the boy* is the agent *and* the subject.
[src:bulgarian-language/agent-grammar] However, when the sentence is rendered in the passive voice, "The ball was kicked by the boy", *the ball* is the grammatical subject, but *the boy* is still the agent.
[src:bulgarian-language/agent-grammar] Many sentences in English and other Indo-European languages have the agent as subject.
[src:bulgarian-language/agent-grammar] The use of some transitive verbs denoting strictly reciprocal events may involve a conflation of agent and subject.
[src:bulgarian-language/agent-grammar] In the sentence "John met Sylvia", for example, though both *John* and *Sylvia* would equally meet Dowty's definition of a Proto-Agent, the co-agent *Sylvia* is downgraded to patient because it is the direct object of the sentence.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p01] Along with the closely related Macedonian language (collectively forming Macedo-Bulgarian), it is a member of the Balkan sprachbund and South Slavic dialect continuum of the Indo-European language family.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p01] The two languages have several characteristics that set them apart from all other Slavic languages, including the elimination of case declension, the development of a suffixed definite article, and the lack of a verb infinitive.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p01] They retain and have further developed the Proto-Slavic verb system (albeit analytically).
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p01] One such major development is the innovation of evidential verb forms to encode for the source of information: witnessed, inferred, or reported.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p01] It is the official language of Bulgaria, and since 2007 has been among the official languages of the European Union.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p01] It is also spoken by the Bulgarian communities in Ukraine, North Macedonia, Moldova, Serbia, Romania, Hungary, Albania, Greece and Turkey.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p01] One can divide the development of the Bulgarian language into several periods.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p01] During the Middle Bulgarian period, the language underwent dramatic changes, losing the Slavonic case system, but preserving the rich verb system (while the development was exactly the opposite in other Slavic languages) and developing a definite article.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p01] It was influenced by its non-Slavic neighbours in the Balkan language area (mostly grammatically) and later also by Turkish, which was the official language of the Ottoman Empire, in the form of the Ottoman Turkish language, mostly lexically.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p01] The damaskin texts mark the transition from Middle Bulgarian to New Bulgarian, which was standardized in the 19th century.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p01] Today one difference between Bulgarian dialects in the country and literary spoken Bulgarian is the significant presence of Old Bulgarian words and even word forms in the latter.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p01] Russian loans are distinguished from Old Bulgarian ones on the basis of the presence of specifically Russian phonetic changes, as in оборот (turnover, rev), непонятен (incomprehensible), ядро (nucleus) and others.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p01] Many other loans from French, English and the classical languages have subsequently entered the language as well.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p01] Modern Bulgarian was based essentially on the Eastern dialects of the language, but its pronunciation is in many respects a compromise between East and West Bulgarian (see especially the phonetic sections below).
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p01] Following the efforts of some figures of the National awakening of Bulgaria (most notably Neofit Rilski and Ivan Bogorov), there had been many attempts to codify a standard Bulgarian language; however, there was much argument surrounding the choice of norms.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p01] Between 1835 and 1878 more than 25 proposals were put forward and "linguistic chaos" ensued.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p01] Eventually the eastern dialects prevailed, and in 1899 the Bulgarian Ministry of Education officially codified a standard Bulgarian language based on the Drinov-Ivanchev orthography.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p01] Bulgarian is the official language of Bulgaria, where it is used in all spheres of public life.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p01] As of 2011, it is spoken as a first language by about 6 million people in the country, or about four out of every five Bulgarian citizens.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p01] There is also a significant Bulgarian diaspora abroad.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p01] One of the main historically established communities are the Bessarabian Bulgarians, whose settlement in the Bessarabia region of nowadays Moldova and Ukraine dates mostly to the early 19th century.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p01] There were 134,000 Bulgarian speakers in Ukraine at the 2001 census, 41,800 in Moldova as of the 2014 census (of which 15,300 were habitual users of the language), and presumably a significant proportion of the 13,200 ethnic Bulgarians residing in neighbouring Transnistria in 2016.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p01] Another community abroad are the Banat Bulgarians, who migrated in the 17th century to the Banat region now split between Romania, Serbia and Hungary.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p01] They speak the Banat Bulgarian dialect, which has had its own written standard and a historically important literary tradition.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p01] There are Bulgarian speakers in neighbouring countries as well.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p01] The regional dialects of Bulgarian and Macedonian form a dialect continuum, and there is no well-defined boundary where one language ends and the other begins.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p01] Within the limits of the Republic of North Macedonia a strong separate Macedonian identity has emerged since the Second World War, even though there still are a small number of citizens who identify their language as Bulgarian.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p01] Beyond the borders of North Macedonia, the situation is more fluid, and the pockets of speakers of the related regional dialects in Albania and in Greece variously identify their language as Macedonian or as Bulgarian.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p01] In Serbia, there were 7,939 speakers as per 2022 census, mainly concentrated in the so-called Western Outlands along the border with Bulgaria.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p01] Bulgarian is also spoken in Turkey: natively by Pomaks, and as a second language by many Bulgarian Turks who emigrated from Bulgaria, mostly during the "Big Excursion" of 1989.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p01] The language is also represented among the diaspora in Western Europe and North America, which has been steadily growing since the 1990s.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p01] Countries with significant numbers of speakers include Germany, Spain, Italy, the United Kingdom (38,500 speakers in England and Wales as of 2011), France, the United States, and Canada (19,100 in 2011).
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p01] In Bulgarian the different reflexes of the yat form the so-called *Yat border* (ятова граница), running approximately from Nikopol on the Danube to Solun (Thessaloniki) on the Aegean Sea.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p01] West of that isogloss, old *yat* is always realized as /ɛ/.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p01] East of it, the reflexes of *yat* prototypically alternate between /ja/ or /ʲa/ (in stressed syllables when not followed by a front vowel) and /ɛ/ (in all other cases).
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p01] The division of the dialects of the Eastern South Slavic into western and eastern subgroup running along the yat border is the most important dividing isogloss there.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p01] The open articulation of yat (as /æ/ or ja) and the reflexes of Proto-Slavic *tj/*ktĭ/*gtĭ and *dj as ⟨щ⟩ (ʃt) and ⟨жд⟩ (ʒd) have traditionally been considered the two most distinctive phonetic features of Old Bulgarian.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p01] The language is mainly split into two broad dialect areas, based on the different reflexes of the Proto-Slavic yat vowel (Ѣ).
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p01] The literary language norm, which is generally based on the Eastern dialects, also has the Eastern alternating reflex of *yat*.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p01] Until 1945, Bulgarian orthography did not reveal this alternation and used the original Old Slavic Cyrillic letter *yat* (Ѣ), which was commonly called двойно е (*dvoyno e*) at the time, to express the historical *yat* vowel or at least root vowels displaying the *ya – e* alternation.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p01] The letter was used in each occurrence of such a root, regardless of the actual pronunciation of the vowel: thus, both *ml**ya**ko* and *ml**e**kar* were spelled with (Ѣ).
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p01] Among other things, this was seen as a way to "reconcile" the Western and the Eastern dialects and maintain language unity at a time when much of Bulgaria's Western dialect area was controlled by Serbia and Greece, but there were still hopes and occasional attempts to recover it.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p01] With the 1945 orthographic reform, this letter was abolished and the present spelling was introduced, reflecting the alternation in pronunciation.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p01] In spite of the literary norm regarding the yat vowel, many people living in Western Bulgaria, including the capital Sofia, will fail to observe its rules.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p01] While the norm requires the realizations *vidyal* vs.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p01] *videli* (he has seen; they have seen), some natives of Western Bulgaria will preserve their local dialect pronunciation with "e" for all instances of "yat" (e.g.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p01] Others, attempting to adhere to the norm, will actually use the "ya" sound even in cases where the standard language has "e" (e.g.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p01] The latter hypercorrection is called свръхякане (*svrah-yakane* ≈"over-*ya*-ing").
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p01] Bulgarian is the only Slavic language whose literary standard does not naturally contain the iotated *e* /jɛ/ (or its variant, *e* after a palatalized consonant /ʲɛ/, except in non-Slavic foreign-loaned words).
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p01] This sound combination is common in all modern Slavic languages (e.g.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p01] Czech *medv**ě**d* /ˈmɛdvjɛt/ "bear", Polish *p**ię**ć* /pjɛɲt͡ɕ/ "five", Serbo-Croatian ***je**len* /jělen/ "deer", Ukrainian *нема**є*** /neˈmajɛ/ "there is not", Macedonian *пишува**ње*** /piˈʃuvaɲʲɛ/ "writing", etc.), as well as some Western Bulgarian dialectal forms – e.g.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p01] *ора̀н**'е*** /oˈraɲʲɛ/ (standard Bulgarian: *оране* /oˈranɛ/, "ploughing"), however it is not represented in standard Bulgarian speech or writing.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p01] Even where /jɛ/ occurs in other Slavic words, in Standard Bulgarian it is usually transcribed and pronounced as pure /ɛ/ – e.g.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p01] Boris Yeltsin is "Eltsin" (Борис Елцин), Yekaterinburg is "Ekaterinburg" (Екатеринбург) and Sarajevo is "Saraevo" (Сараево), although – because of the stress and the beginning of the word – Jelena Janković is "**Ye**lena Yankovich" (Йелена Янкович).
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p01] Until the period immediately following the Second World War, all Bulgarian and the majority of foreign linguists referred to the South Slavic dialect continuum spanning the area of modern Bulgaria, North Macedonia and parts of Northern Greece as a group of Bulgarian dialects.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p01] In contrast, Serbian sources tended to label them "south Serbian" dialects.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p01] Some local naming conventions included *bolgárski*, *bugárski* and so forth.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p01] The codifiers of the standard Bulgarian language, however, did not wish to make any allowances for a pluricentric "Bulgaro-Macedonian" compromise.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p01] After 1944 the People's Republic of Bulgaria and the Socialist Federal Republic of Yugoslavia began a policy of making Macedonia into the connecting link for the establishment of a new Balkan Federative Republic and stimulating here a development of distinct Macedonian consciousness.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p01] With the proclamation of the Socialist Republic of Macedonia as part of the Yugoslav federation, the new authorities also started measures that would overcome the pro-Bulgarian feeling among parts of its population and in 1945 a separate Macedonian language was codified.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p01] After 1958, when the pressure from Moscow decreased, Sofia reverted to the view that the Macedonian language did not exist as a separate language.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p01] Nowadays, Bulgarian and Greek linguists, as well as some linguists from other countries, still consider the various Macedonian dialects as part of the broader Bulgarian pluricentric dialectal continuum.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p01] Outside Bulgaria and Greece, Macedonian is generally considered an autonomous language within the South Slavic dialect continuum.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p01] Sociolinguists agree that the question whether Macedonian is a dialect of Bulgarian or a language is a political one and cannot be resolved on a purely linguistic basis, because dialect continua do not allow for either/or judgements.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p01] Bulgarian possesses a phonology similar to that of the rest of the South Slavic languages, notably lacking Serbo-Croatian's phonemic vowel length and tones and alveolo-palatal affricates.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p01] Both patterns have partial parallels in Russian, leading to partially similar sounds.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p01] In turn, the Western dialects generally do not have any allophonic palatalization and exhibit minor, if any, vowel reduction.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p01] Standard Bulgarian keeps a middle ground between the macrodialects.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p01] It allows palatalizaton only before central and back vowels and only partial reduction of /a/ and /ɔ/.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p01] Reduction of /ɛ/, consonant palatalisation before front vowels and depalatalization of palatalized consonants before central and back vowels is strongly discouraged and labelled as provincial.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p01] Bulgarian has six vowel phonemes, but at least eight distinct phones can be distinguished when reduced allophones are taken into consideration.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p01] There is currently no consensus on the number of Bulgarian consonants, with one school of thought advocating for the existence of only 22 consonant phonemes and another one claiming that there are not fewer than 39 consonant phonemes.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p01] The main bone of contention is how to treat palatalized consonants: as separate phonemes or as allophones of their respective plain counterparts.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p01] The 22-consonant model is based on a general consensus reached by all major Bulgarian linguists in the 1930s and 1940s.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p01] In turn, the 39-consonant model was launched in the beginning of the 1950s under the influence of the ideas of Russian linguist Nikolai Trubetzkoy.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p01] Despite frequent objections, the support of the Bulgarian Academy of Sciences has ensured Trubetzkoy's model virtual monopoly in state-issued phonologies and grammars since the 1960s.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p01] However, its reception abroad has been lukewarm, with a number of authors either calling the model into question or outright rejecting it.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p01] Thus, the Handbook of the International Phonetic Association only lists 22 consonants in Bulgarian's consonant inventory.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p01] In 886 AD, the Bulgarian Empire introduced the Glagolitic alphabet which was devised by the Saints Cyril and Methodius in the 850s.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p01] The Glagolitic alphabet was gradually superseded in later centuries by the Cyrillic script, developed around the Preslav Literary School, Bulgaria in the late 9th century.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p01] Several Cyrillic alphabets with 28 to 44 letters were used in the beginning and the middle of the 19th century during the efforts on the codification of Modern Bulgarian until an alphabet with 32 letters, proposed by Marin Drinov, gained prominence in the 1870s.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p01] The alphabet of Marin Drinov was used until the orthographic reform of 1945, when the letters yat (uppercase Ѣ, lowercase ѣ) and big yus (uppercase Ѫ, lowercase ѫ) were removed from its alphabet, reducing the number of letters to 30.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p01] With the accession of Bulgaria to the European Union on 1 January 2007, Cyrillic became the third official script of the European Union, following the Latin and Greek scripts.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] The parts of speech in Bulgarian are divided in ten types, which are categorized in two broad classes: mutable and immutable.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] The difference is that mutable parts of speech vary grammatically, whereas the immutable ones do not change, regardless of their use.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] The five classes of mutables are: *nouns*, *adjectives*, *numerals*, *pronouns* and *verbs*.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] Syntactically, the first four of these form the group of the noun or the nominal group.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] The immutables are: *adverbs*, *prepositions*, *conjunctions*, *particles* and *interjections*.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] Verbs and adverbs form the group of the verb or the verbal group.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] Nouns and adjectives have the categories grammatical gender, number, case (only vocative) and definiteness in Bulgarian.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] Adjectives and adjectival pronouns agree with nouns in number and gender.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] Pronouns have gender and number and retain (as in nearly all Indo-European languages) a more significant part of the case system.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] There are three grammatical genders in Bulgarian: *masculine*, *feminine* and *neuter*.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] There are also some commonly used words that end in a vowel and yet are masculine: баща 'father', дядо 'grandfather', чичо / вуйчо 'uncle', and others.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] Also, the plural ending –ове /ovɛ/ occurs only in masculine nouns.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] Two numbers are distinguished in Bulgarian–singular and plural.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] A variety of plural suffixes is used, and the choice between them is partly determined by their ending in singular and partly influenced by gender; in addition, irregular declension and alternative plural forms are common.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] Words ending in –а/–я (which are usually feminine) generally have the plural ending –и, upon dropping of the singular ending.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] Of nouns ending in a consonant, the feminine ones also use –и, whereas the masculine ones usually have –и for polysyllables and –ове for monosyllables (however, exceptions are especially common in this group).
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] Nouns ending in –о/–е (most of which are neuter) mostly use the suffixes –а, –я (both of which require the dropping of the singular endings) and –та.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] However, a recently developed language norm requires that count forms should only be used with masculine nouns that do not denote persons.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] Thus, двама/трима ученици ('two/three students') is perceived as more correct than двама/трима ученика, while the distinction is retained in cases such as два/три молива ('two/three pencils') versus тези моливи ('these pencils').
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] Cases exist only in the personal and some other pronouns (as they do in many other modern Indo-European languages), with nominative, accusative, dative and vocative forms.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] Vestiges are present in a number of phraseological units and sayings.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] The major exception are vocative forms, which are still in use for masculine (with the endings -е, -о and -ю) and feminine nouns (-[ь/й]о and -е) in the singular.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] There are four singular definite articles.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] Again, the choice between them is largely determined by the noun's ending in the singular.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] Nouns that end in a consonant and are masculine use –ът/–ят, when they are grammatical subjects, and –а/–я elsewhere.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] Nouns that end in a consonant and are feminine, as well as nouns that end in –а/–я (most of which are feminine, too) use –та.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] The plural definite article is –те for all nouns except for plural forms that end in –а/–я; getting –та instead.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] When postfixed to adjectives the definite articles are –ят/–я for masculine gender (again, with the longer form being reserved for grammatical subjects), –та for feminine gender, –то for neuter gender, and –те for plural.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] Both groups agree in gender and number with the noun they are appended to.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] They may also take the definite article as explained above.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] Pronouns may vary in gender, number, and definiteness, and are the only parts of speech that have retained case inflections.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] Three cases are exhibited by some groups of pronouns – nominative, accusative and dative.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] The distinguishable types of pronouns include the following: personal, relative, reflexive, interrogative, negative, indefinite, summative and possessive.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] A Bulgarian verb has many distinct forms, as it varies in person, number, voice, aspect, mood, tense and in some cases gender.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] Finite verbal forms are *simple* or *compound* and agree with subjects in person (first, second and third) and number (singular, plural).
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] In addition to that, past compound forms using participles vary in gender (masculine, feminine, neuter) and voice (active and passive) as well as aspect (perfective/aorist and imperfective).
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] Bulgarian verbs express lexical aspect: perfective verbs signify the completion of the action of the verb and form past perfective (aorist) forms; imperfective ones are neutral with regard to it and form past imperfective forms.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] Most Bulgarian verbs can be grouped in perfective-imperfective pairs (imperfective/perfective: идвам/дойда "come", пристигам/пристигна "arrive").
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] Perfective verbs can be usually formed from imperfective ones by suffixation or prefixation, but the resultant verb often deviates in meaning from the original.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] In the pair examples above, aspect is stem-specific and therefore there is no difference in meaning.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] In Bulgarian, there is also grammatical aspect.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] Three grammatical aspects are distinguishable: neutral, perfect and pluperfect.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] The neutral aspect comprises the three simple tenses and the future tense.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] The pluperfect is manifest in tenses that use double or triple auxiliary "be" participles like the past pluperfect subjunctive.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] Perfect constructions use a single auxiliary "be".
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] The possible existence of a few other moods has been discussed in the literature.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] Most Bulgarian school grammars teach the traditional view of 4 Bulgarian moods (as described above, but excluding the subjunctive and including the inferential).
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] There are three grammatically distinctive positions in time – present, past and future – which combine with aspect and mood to produce a number of formations.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] Normally, in grammar books these formations are viewed as separate tenses – i. e.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] "past imperfect" would mean that the verb is in past tense, in the imperfective aspect, and in the indicative mood (since no other mood is shown).
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] There are more than 40 different tenses across Bulgarian's two aspects and five moods.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] The four perfect constructions above can vary in aspect depending on the aspect of the main-verb participle; they are in fact pairs of imperfective and perfective aspects.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] Verbs in forms using past participles also vary in voice and gender.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] There are compound imperative forms for all persons and numbers in the present compound imperative (да играе, da iɡˈrae/), the present perfect compound imperative (да е играл, /dɐ ɛ iɡˈraɫ/) and the rarely used present pluperfect compound imperative (да е бил играл, /dɐ ɛ bil iɡˈraɫ/).
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] The conditional mood consists of five compound tenses, most of which are not grammatically distinguishable.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] The present, future and past conditional use a special past form of the stem би- (bi – "be") and the past participle (бих учил, /bix ˈutʃiɫ/, 'I would study').
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] The past future conditional and the past future perfect conditional coincide in form with the respective indicative tenses.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] The subjunctive mood is rarely documented as a separate verb form in Bulgarian (being, morphologically, a sub-instance of the quasi-infinitive construction with the particle да and a normal finite verb form), but nevertheless it is used regularly.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] The most common form, often mistaken for the present tense, is the present subjunctive ([по-добре] да отида (ˈpɔdobrɛ) dɐ oˈtidɐ/, 'I had better go').
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] The difference between the present indicative and the present subjunctive tense is that the subjunctive can be formed by *both* perfective and imperfective verbs.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] It has completely replaced the infinitive and the supine from complex expressions (see below).
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] It is also employed to express opinion about *possible* future events.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] The inferential mood has five pure tenses.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] Two of them are simple – *past aorist inferential* and *past imperfect inferential* – and are formed by the past participles of perfective and imperfective verbs, respectively.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] There are also three compound tenses – *past future inferential*, *past future perfect inferential* and *past perfect inferential*.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] All these tenses' forms are gender-specific in the singular.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] There are also conditional and compound-imperative crossovers.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] The existence of inferential forms has been attributed to Turkic influences by most Bulgarian linguists.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] Morphologically, they are derived from the perfect.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] The participles are inflected by gender, number, and definiteness, and are coordinated with the subject when forming compound tenses (see tenses above).
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] When used in an attributive role, the inflection attributes are coordinated with the noun that is being attributed.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] Bulgarian uses reflexive verbal forms (i.e. actions which are performed by the agent onto him- or herself) which behave in a similar way as they do in many other Indo-European languages, such as French and Spanish.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] The reflexive is expressed by the invariable particle ***se***, originally a clitic form of the accusative reflexive pronoun.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] The same pattern is used to form adverbs from the (adjective-like) ordinal numerals, e.g. първо (firstly), второ (secondly), трето (thirdly), and in some cases from (adjective-like) cardinal numerals, e.g. двойно (twice as/double), тройно (three times as), петорно (five times as).
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] The remaining adverbs are formed in ways that are no longer productive in the language.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] A small number are original (not derived from other words), for example: тук (here), там (there), вътре (inside), вън (outside), много (very/much) etc.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] Adverbs can sometimes be reduplicated to emphasize the qualitative or quantitative properties of actions, moods or relations as performed by the subject of the sentence: "бавно-бавно" ("rather slowly"), "едва-едва" ("with great difficulty"), "съвсем-съвсем" ("quite", "thoroughly").
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] In Bulgarian, there are several conjunctions all translating into English as "but", which are all used in distinct situations.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] They are но (*no*), ама (*amà*), а (*a*), ами (*amì*), and ала (*alà*) (and обаче (*obache*) – "however", identical in use to но).
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] While there is some overlapping between their uses, in many cases they are specific.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] For example, *ami* is used for a choice – *ne tova, ami onova* – "not this one, but that one" (compare Spanish *sino*), while *ama* is often used to provide extra information or an opinion – *kazah go, ama sgreshih* – "I said it, but I was wrong".
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] Meanwhile, *a* provides contrast between two situations, and in some sentences can even be translated as "although", "while" or even "and" – *az rabotya, a toy blee* – "I'm working, and he's daydreaming".
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] Similarly, *az ne iskam, ama toy iska* and *az ne iskam, a toy iska* both mean "I don't want to, but he does", however the first emphasizes the fact that *he* wants to, while the second emphasizes the *wanting* rather than the person.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] Bulgarian has several abstract particles which are used to strengthen a statement.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] These have no precise translation in English.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] The particles are strictly informal and can even be considered rude by some people and in some situations.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] They are mostly used at the end of questions or instructions.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] These are "tagged" on to the beginning or end of a sentence to express the mood of the speaker in relation to the situation.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] They are mostly interrogative or slightly imperative in nature.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] There is no change in the grammatical mood when these are used (although they may be expressed through different grammatical moods in other languages).
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] These express intent or desire, perhaps even pleading.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] They can be seen as a sort of cohortative side to the language.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] (Since they can be used by themselves, they could even be considered as verbs in their own right.) They are also highly informal.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] These particles can be combined with the vocative particles for greater effect, e.g.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] *ya da vidya, be* (let me see), or even exclusively in combinations with them, with no other elements, e.g.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] *hayde, de!* (come on!); *nedey, de!* (I told you not to!).
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] The adjective *ednakuv* ("the same") derives from the same radical.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] An interesting phenomenon is that these can be strung along one after another in quite long constructions, e.g.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] The subject of the sentence is simply the pronoun "*taya*" (lit.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] Another interesting phenomenon that is observed in colloquial speech is the use of *takova* (neuter of *takyv*) not only as a substitute for an adjective, but also as a substitute for a verb.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] In that case the base form *takova* is used as the third person singular in the present indicative and all other forms are formed by analogy to other verbs in the language.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] Sometimes the "verb" may even acquire a derivational prefix that changes its meaning.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] As a result of this versatility, the word *takova* can readily be used as a euphemism for taboo subjects.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] Similar "meaningless" expressions are extremely common in spoken Bulgarian, especially when the speaker is finding it difficult to describe or express something.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] Bulgarian employs clitic doubling, mostly for emphatic purposes.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] Transl.: "Petar and Ivan were eaten by the wolves".
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] Transl.: "Petar and Ivan ate the wolves".
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] Petar and Ivan were eaten by the wolves.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] На мен ми се спи, а на Иван му се играе.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] На нас ни е студено, а на вас ви е топло.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] Иван го боли гърлото, а мене ме боли главата.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] Transl.: Ivan has sore throat, and I have a headache.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] Except the above examples, clitic doubling is considered inappropriate in a formal context.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] Most of the vocabulary of modern Bulgarian consists of terms inherited from Proto-Slavic and local Bulgarian innovations and formations of those through the mediation of Old and Middle Bulgarian.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] The native terms in Bulgarian account for 70% to 80% of the lexicon.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] The remaining 20% to 30% are loanwords from a number of languages, as well as derivations of such words.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] Bulgarian adopted also a few words of Thracian and Bulgar origin.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] The classical languages Latin and Greek are the source of many words, used mostly in international terminology.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] Many Latin terms entered Bulgarian during the time when present-day Bulgaria was part of the Roman Empire and also in the later centuries through Romanian, Aromanian, and Megleno-Romanian during Bulgarian Empires.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] The loanwords of Greek origin in Bulgarian are a product of the influence of the liturgical language of the Orthodox Church.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] Many of the numerous loanwords from another Turkic language, Ottoman Turkish and, via Ottoman Turkish, from Arabic were adopted into Bulgarian during the long period of Ottoman rule, but have been replaced with native Bulgarian terms.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] Furthermore, after the independence of Bulgaria from the Ottoman Empire in 1878, Bulgarian intellectuals imported many French language vocabulary.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] In addition, both specialized (usually coming from the field of science) and commonplace English words (notably abstract, commodity/service-related or technical terms) have also penetrated Bulgarian since the second half of the 20th century, especially since 1989.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] A growing number of international neologisms are also being widely adopted, causing controversy between younger generations who, in general, are raised in the era of digital globalization, and the older, more conservative educated purists.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] Всички хора се раждат свободни и равни по достойнство и права. Те са надарени с разум и съвест и следва да се отнасят помежду си в дух на братство.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] Vsichki hora se razhdat svobodni i ravni po dostoynstvo i prava.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] Te sa nadareni s razum i sŭvest i sledva da se otnasyat pomezhdu si v duh na bratstvo.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] ['fsit͡ʃki 'xɔrɐ sɛ 'raʒdɐt svo'bɔdni i 'ravni po dos'tɔjnstvo i prɐ'va.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] All human beings are born free and equal in dignity and rights.
[src:bulgarian-language/bulgarian-language-p02] They are endowed with reason and conscience and should act towards one another in a spirit of brotherhood.
